<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000GMT, Thursday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Accused German businessman Helmut Hofer has been
ordered on remand pending investigations into remaining charges
against him.
</P>
<P>
The Public Relations Office of Tehran's Justice Department
issued a statement Thursday, saying Hofer, who was cleared of
illicit sexual affairs, will remain in jail temporarily.
</P>
<P>
Hofer finally escaped a possible death penalty Wednesday after
standing a third trial at a Tehran public court, which dropped the
adultery charge against him. (BC-Iran-Germany-Businessman)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GAZA -- A senior Palestinian official Thursday denied a
reported secret agreement between Palestinian National Authority
and Israel on the issue of settlements and commencement of final
status negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Culture and Information Yasser Abed Rabbo, also
leader of the Palestinian delegation to the final status talks,
told the "Voice of Palestine" radio that the settlement issue
constitutes the first priority of the Palestinian Authority.
(BC-Palestine-Israel)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GAZA -- Senior Palestinian and Israeli officials on Thursday
began their talks on the release of a third batch of Palestinian
prisoners from Israeli jails.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Minister of State for Prisoners Affairs Hisham
Abdul Raziq met with Israeli Minister of Justice Yossi Beilin to
discuss the matter.
</P>
<P>
Raziq told reporters that in accordance with the Sharm
el-Sheikh Memorandum, approved by the Palestinian and Israeli
sides earlier this month, the third batch is to be released on
October 8. (BC-Palestine-Israel-Prisoners)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- In a further sign of improved relations, Egypt
announced on Thursday that it will, for the first time in 20
years, take part in an international exhibition in the Iranian
capital of Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Tehran severed diplomatic ties with Cairo in 1979 after Egypt
signed a peace treaty with Israel, an arch enemy of the Islamic
republic. (BC-Egypt-Iran-Exhibition)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein on Thursday received
a letter from his Russian counterpart Boris Yeltsin in which
Yeltsin said Russia would work for the lifting of the United
Nations sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's letter was conveyed to Saddam during his meeting
with visiting Russian Minister of Fuel and Energy Victor
Kalyuzhni, who arrived here Tuesday evening to attend the third
session of the Iraqi-Russian Economic, Trade and Technical Joint
Committee. (BC-Iraq-Saddam-Russia) 
</P>
