<HEADLINE> Nyerere Starts to Gain Strength Under Medical </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The founding father of
Tanzania Julius Nyerere who is seriously ill and admitted at St.
Thomas Hospital in London, has gained more strength following
medication administered to him through nasal gastric tube.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the President's Press Secretary Geoffrey
Nkurlu in Dar es Salaam Thursday said that Nyerere has been able
to open his eyes now and then able to turn sides without
assistance.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, doctors attending the 77-year-old
Nyerere, who is suffering chronic lymphocytic leukemia, have
managed to contain minor breathing problems.
</P>
<P>
It further said that the doctors on Thursday took more blood
tests in order to make further investigations of jaundice that has
developed since Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to Tanzanian High Commissioner to Britain Sharrif
Abdul Kadri, Nyerere's condition is improving steadily.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere, who was admitted to the hospital last Friday, is under
round- the-clock medical care, while his wife Maria Nyerere and
his two daughters Anna Nyerere and Rose Nyerere are taking turns
in assisting him.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian government is trying to get the best treatment
available in Britain for Nyerere and President Benjamin Mkapa is
closely monitoring the elder African statesman's condition.
</P>
<P>
Kingunge Ngombale-Mwiru, minister of Administration and Local
Government, left Tanzanian capital Dar es Salaam for London
Tuesday to administer issues concerning Nyerere in collaboration
with Tanzanian High Commission in Britain.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere led the then Tanganyika to independence from Britain in
1961 and masterminded its union Zanzibar isles in 1964 to form
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
After retiring as president in 1985, he played an advisory role
in both Tanzanian politics and African affairs. He tirelessly
mediated Burundi peace talks in the past four years.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa has asked the nation to pray for Nyerere, who is highly
respected as Mwalimu or teacher in Kiswahili language. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
