<HEADLINE> Cohen Orders Investigation into S.Korea Massacre Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Defense Secretary William
Cohen on Thursday ordered the Army to investigate reports about
U.S. soldiers gunning down civilians in the Korean War in 1950.
</P>
<P>
Cohen wrote a letter to Army Secretary Louis Caldera, asking
him to "determine the full scope of the facts surrounding press
reports of civilian deaths" in No Gun Ri village south of Seoul in
the early days of the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
"These reports are of course very disturbing,"Caldera told a
Pentagon news briefing. He said a new review would be conducted,
which would go beyond looking at historical records and include
interviewing soldiers from the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
The new review was ordered after an Associated Press report
quoted villagers and U.S. veterans saying that hundreds, including
women and children, were killed by the U.S. military in the
southeastern village of No Gun Ri on July 26-29, 1950. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
