<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Rwandan Cabinet Ministers Involved in Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 30 (Xinhua) -- A parliamentary commission of
Rwanda presented a report Wednesday to investigate a corruption
case in which the government lost one million U.S. dollars,
Rwandan News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The three high officials concerned are Minister of Social
Affairs Charles Ntakirutinka, Minister of Commerce Mark Rugenera
and Minister in President's Office in charge of Institutional
Relations Anastase Gasana.
</P>
<P>
"The results of the investigation of the commission are
conclusive," Joseph Sebarenzi, speaker of the National Assembly,
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said that the next move is to summon these ministers to
parliament to explain themselves about their involvement.
</P>
<P>
"If their arguments are not sufficient, a vote of
non-confidence will be made, and the three ministers will be asked
to resign from their posts," one lawmaker said.
</P>
<P>
The affair in which the three ministers are involved relates to
the purchase of government vehicles in 1996 by the then Minister
of Public Works Ntakirutinka.
</P>
<P>
The deal was first signed with a local procurement company
before Ntakirutinka illegally passed the deal to another
businessman for a heavy craft with the connivance of the then
Minister of Finance Rugenera.
</P>
<P>
The probe of the three ministers followed that of Emmanuel
Mudidi, minister of Education, into another affair of embezzling
26 million U.S. dollars from a project financed by the World Bank
for the rehabilitation of schools after the genocide.
</P>
<P>
Patrick Mazimhaka, minister in President's Office, will also be
summoned in the near future to explain the mismanagement that
rocked the Ministry of Rehabilitation he was heading.
</P>
<P>
"Our government has a good will to usher in good governance,"
Sebarenzi said, adding that their action will help stem the rising
corruption in government's institutions by inciting ministers to
be accountable in their responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that ministers will be more careful when they note
that some of their colleagues are punished politically," Sebarenzi
concluded.  
</P>
</TEXT>
