<HEADLINE> Clinton Briefed over S. Korea Massacre Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 30 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton was
briefed on the Associated Press report about U.S. soldiers gunning
down civilians in the Korean War in 1950 and said he endorsed
Defense Secretary William Cohen's order to investigate the mass
killing.
</P>
<P>
Cohen wrote a letter to Army Secretary Louis Caldera on
Thursday, asking him to "determine the full scope of the facts
surrounding press reports of civilian deaths" in No gun Ri village
south of Seoul in the early days of the Korea War.
</P>
<P>
Clinton told reporters at the White House that Cohen "wants to
get to the bottom of it."
</P>
<P>
"he wants to examine all the available information and
evidence," he said.
</P>
<P>
Caldera admitted at a pentagon news briefing that the reports
"are of course very disturbing." He promised a "complete and
thorough review" of accounts of the mass killings.
</P>
<P>
He said a new review would be conducted, which would go beyond
looking at historical records and include interviewing soldiers
from the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
The new review was ordered after an Associated Press report
quoted villagers and U.S. veterans saying that hundreds, including
women and children, were killed by the U.S. military in the
southeastern village of No Gun Ri on July 26-29, 1950. 
</P>
</TEXT>
