<HEADLINE> Former U.N. Staff Member Convicted of Fraud Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 30 (Xinhua) -- A jury in a Manhattan
Federal Court Tuesday found a former U.N. staff member guilty on
all five counts of wire fraud and conspiracy stemming from his
participation in schemes to defraud the United Nations, a U.N.
spokesman said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The individual, Charles Kim, submitted fraudulent and inflated
travel charges to the United Nations from 1996 until September
1998 resulting in a loss to the organization of some 800,000 U.S.
dollars," U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
Eckhard told a press conference here that Kim's felony
conviction was made possible following a complex and thorough
investigation by the Investigations Section of the Office of
Internal Oversight Services (OIOS).
</P>
<P>
Investigators from that section worked overtime to gather both
documentary and testimonial evidence against Kim which was then
referred to U.S. and Croatian authorities, he said.
</P>
<P>
Several U.N. staff members, including one staff of the Bosnian
Mission and one of the OIOS investigators, provided testimony
during Kim's trial, he said.
</P>
<P>
Kim is scheduled to be sentenced on December 8. He faces a
maximum penalty on each of the five counts of five years in
prison, the spokesman added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
