<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt to Attend Iranian Fair for First Time in Two </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 30 (Xinhua) -- In a further sign of improved
relations, Egypt announced on Thursday that it will, for the first
time in 20 years, take part in an international exhibition in the
Iranian capital of Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Tehran severed diplomatic ties with Cairo in 1979 after Egypt
signed a peace treaty with Israel, an arch enemy of the Islamic
republic.
</P>
<P>
Ever since, Egypt and Iran have been maintaining low-level
economic and trade ties. In the recent two years, the two
countries have repeatedly expressed readiness to mend fences and
exchanged visits by political and cultural delegations.
</P>
<P>
Some 31 major Egyptian companies will attend the 10-day Tehran
exhibition slated for Friday, Board Chairman of Egypt's General
Organization of Exhibition and International Markets Mohamed Said
Saleh said.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian pavilion will cover an area of 700 square meters,
which is one of the largest among the participants, Saleh said in
remarks carried by the country's Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian firms will showcase products including engineering
equipment, food, medicines and ready-made clothes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
