<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Condemns Fresh Turkish Incursion of Northern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Foreign Ministry on
Thursday condemned the fresh Turkish troops incursion of northern
Iraq, urging the Turkish government to withdraw its troops
immediately.
</P>
<P>
A Foreign Ministry spokesman said in a statement that on
Tuesday, some 5,000 Turkish troops, supported by tanks, armored
vehicles, helicopters and warplanes, invaded the northern Iraqi
territories.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Iraq vehemently protests against and
condemns Turkey's new military invasion and violation of Iraq's
sovereignty and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
"This invasion is part of repeated series carried out by the
Turkish forces against Iraq since 1991 and is coincided with the
feverish military aggression acts being perpetrated by America
and Britain against Iraq," he said.
</P>
<P>
He called upon the Turkish government to withdraw its troops
immediately and desist from repeating such aggressive acts which
are contrary to the United Nations Charter and principles of the
international law.
</P>
<P>
After the 1991 Gulf War, the Iraqi government lost its control
of the northern Kurdish autonomous region, and Turkish government
troops often cross the border into northern Iraq to chase rebels
of the outlawed Turkish Kurdish Workers' Party.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi spokesman also warned against the Turkish assistance
it offers to the United States and British warplanes to carry out
raids on northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led western allies imposed two no-fly zones in Iraq
following the Gulf War with a claimed aim of protecting the Kurds
in the north and Shiite Muslims in the south from possible attacks
by the Iraqi government troops.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi spokesman warned that "the Iraqi government retains
its full right to retaliate this aggressive act in proper time
and venue." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
