<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAO Chief Calls for Strategy Against Hunger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Dr. Jacques Diouf,
director general of the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO),
Thursday called on developing countries to prepare strategies
against hunger.
</P>
<P>
Before ending his three-day visit to Tanzania, Diouf told a
meeting in the capital Dar es Salaam that developing countries
should build water- control facilities, especially small-scale
ones that can be constructed at affordable cost.
</P>
<P>
He said an irrigation scheme built with 10,000 U.S. dollars in
Mkindo village and a pedal pump in the Hembeti village in the
Morogoro Region in central Tanzania, where he visited Wednesday,
are very impressing.
</P>
<P>
Both of the projects are part of the Special Program for Food
Security (SPFS) launched by FAO in collaboration with relevant
countries and international organizations.
</P>
<P>
The program, launched in 1994 with 3.5 million U.S. dollars,
has currently covered 49 countries and gained much greater
strength. The goal of FAO is to make 122 developing countries
benefit from the program.
</P>
<P>
In Morogoro Region, the FAO director general also visited
several groups formed by villagers who have gained income through
raising chicken, goat and sheep or planting maize, pigeon beans
and rice. The groups have got technical or financial assistance
from SPFS.
</P>
<P>
Diouf said diversification is an important strategy, noting
that raising poultry or planting crops with improved species is a
component part of food security strategy.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he called on developing countries to build roads
and warehouses to enable farmers to transport their agriculture
produce to the market and store their grain.
</P>
<P>
The director general stressed that South-south cooperation is
important for solving food problem. He commended the technical
assistance to Tanzanian peasants by Egyptian agriculture experts.
</P>
<P>
He called on agriculture experts to "go to the field" to help
farmers instead of staying in the office.
</P>
<P>
Diouf, who visited Tanzania with a 30-odd delegation which
consists of ambassadors and senior agriculture officials from
different countries, appealed for extension services and financial
assistance to farmers.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, which arrived in Dar es Salaam on Tuesday, has
come to Tanzania to get information about how SPFS is carried out
in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Diouf held talks with Tanzanian President Benjamin
Mkapa and Prime Minister Frederick Sumaye.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's Deputy Minister of Agriculture and Co-operatives
Ismail Ivwata said that his country, which suffers from food
shortages, will extend the program to all regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
