<HEADLINE> 30 Men Jailed in Egypt for Arms Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 30 (Xinhua) -- An Egyptian court on Thursday
sentenced 29 Egyptians and one Libyan to prison terms ranging
between one and five years for smuggling and illegally trading
arms.
</P>
<P>
The Alexandria State Security Court sentenced three men,
including the Libyan to five years in prison with labor, the
country's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Four others were sentenced in absentia to the same jail terms
by the court in the Mediterranean port city, 220 kilometers
northwest of Cairo, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-three got one to three years in jail for aiding and
illegally acquiring the weapons, it added.
</P>
<P>
Six of the defendants were acquitted by the court.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen of the men were arrested on April 26 as they tried to
cross into Egypt from Libya through the el-Salloum checkpoint.
Police confiscated 52 guns and an automatic rifle from their
truck. Seventeen others had been identified by the 13 defendants
during interrogations.
</P>
<P>
The men bought the weapons from Omar al-Salmani, a Libyan
soldier who worked as a guard of a Libyan weapons
depot. Al-Salmani is reported to have been executed recently in
Libya for stealing weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
