<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The United States said
on Thursday that it was closely monitoring reports about a
nuclear accident at a Japanese uranium processing plant and
would be in touch with Japanese officials about it.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously this is a very serious situation," said David
Leavy, spokesman for the White House National Security Council.
"We're watching it closely."
</P>
<P>
The accident took place earlier in the day at Tokaimura in
Ibaraki Prefecture, about 140 km northeast of Tokyo, exposing 19
people to radiation and prompted authorities to evacuate the
area.
</P>
<P>
Leavy said the United States had not yet received any
official request for assistance from Japan, "but we'll be in
touch with Japanese officials."
</P>
<P>
Japan's Kyodo news agency quoted senior government officials
as saying that Japan lacked experience in dealing with this kind
of accident and was considering seeking help from the U.S.
military who may have the necessary know-how.
</P>
<P>
But a Pentagon spokesman said they had not yet got anything
from Japan about the accident. 
