<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- Foreign oil companies operating in Yemen are enhancing
their prospecting and production programs for the years ahead,
Egypt's Arab daily Al Hayat reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Yemeni Undersecretary of State for Petroleum and Mineral Wealth
Rasheed Barba'a anticipates that several prospecting sectors will
turn to production in the coming few years. The crude oil
production in Yemen is 400,000 barrels per day, he disclosed.
</P>
<P>
JEDDA -- The "Jedda International Fairs" company has obtained
the approval of Saudi authorities to organize a fair for Saudi
industries in the Yemeni capital Aden during the first quarter of
next year, Al Hayat reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The company's managing director Hasan Al Harthi also said his
company has completed all preparatory works for the "made-in-Saudi
Arabia" fair which will take place at the Tehran International
Fairs Center in the Iranian capital city in mid-November.
</P>
<P>
DUBAI -- Petroleum sources said the Bahari Natural Gas field
discovered two months ago by "Hilal Petroleum" company offshore
the emirate of Sharja, United Arab Emirates (UAE), has huge
deposits of natural gas, Al Hayat reported.
</P>
<P>
The sources estimated that the deposits of natural gas at the
field is more than 400 billion cubic feet. Production tests are
to begin within the coming three months.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- A recent World Labor Organization survey has put the
official number of unemployment in the Arab world at over 12
million, or 14 percent of the Arab population, Al Kifah al Arabi
newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
The lastest figures were disclosed Monday at a conference in
Beirut on unemployment organized by WLO's regional office.
</P>
<P>
Around 40 percent of those unemployed are young men and women,
the survey noted. 
</P>
