<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at GMT 1600, September 30 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA -- The Indonesian Military (TNI) forbade the
International Force for East Timor (Interfet) from entering West
Timor (Indonesia's Province of East Nusa Tenggara), TNI spokesman
Major General Sudrajat told reporters Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"If the Interfet wants to chase militia to West Timor, it
should make coordination first, it (Interfet) cannot enter the
province without permission," Sudrajat said prior to a meeting
between TNI Commander/Defense Minister General Wiranto with
visiting U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen here. (Indonesia-
Interfet-West Timor)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- A safe passage between the West Bank and Gaza
Strip will be opened Sunday as scheduled in the latest Israeli-
Palestinian peace agreement, Prime Minister Ehud Barak said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"This subject has been discussed from every possible angle over
the years. Now the time has come to carry it out according to the
agreement that has been signed," Barak said during a visit to the
Northern Command of the Israeli army.
</P>
<P>
The safe passage, which links the Gaza Strip with the West Bank
city of Hebron, will enable Palestinians to travel and transport
goods between the Palestinian self-rule areas for the first time.
(Israel-Palestine-Safe Passage)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Visiting U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen
Thursday urged the Indonesian Military (TNI) to make the right
choice in the East Timor problem.
</P>
<P>
"The Indonesian military will be acting in a manner consistent
with Indonesia's national interests and international obligations
if they contribute to a peaceful solution in East Timor," Cohen
said at a press conference held here Thursday afternoon. (
Indonesia-U.S.-Cohen)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi said Thursday
night he would postpone the cabinet reshuffle scheduled for Friday
due to an unprecedented nuclear accident in Ibaraki Prefecture,
northeast of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi made the remarks to a group of reporters after convening
a high-level emergency meeting on a radiation leak at a uranium
processing plant in Tokaimura, where radiation levels at and
around the plant remained high. (Japan-Cabinet-Nuclear Accident)
</P>
</TEXT>
