<HEADLINE> U.S. Massacre of Civilians in Korean War Described </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. soldiers
machine-gunned hundreds of helpless civilians under a railroad
bridge in South Korea early in the Korean War, the Associated
Press said.
</P>
<P>
The terrible episode was reported by the AP Wednesday and
carried by main American newspapers including the New York Times
and the Washington Post Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The news agency said when South Korean survivors and victims'
relatives told their story, and sought redress, they met only
rejection and denial, from the U.S. military and their own
government in Seoul.
</P>
<P>
The AP spent months tracing American veterans in some 130
interviews by telephone and in person, and a dozen former U.S.
soldiers have spoken out. Although none gave a complete, detailed
account of the events under the bridge near No Gun Ri some 160
kilometers southeast of Seoul in 1950, their memories support the
villagers' accounts.
</P>
<P>
In late July 1950, the American veterans said, their Army
battalion killed a large number of South Korean refugees at a
hamlet near No Gun Ri.
</P>
<P>
The former U.S. soldiers spoke of 100, 200 or simply hundreds
dead. The Koreans, whose claim for compensation was rejected last
year, said 300 were shot to death after 100 had been killed in an
air attack.
</P>
<P>
American commanders had ordered units in retreat in the Korean
War's first desperate weeks to shoot civilians as a defense
against disguised enemy soldiers, according to once-classified
documents found by the AP in months of researching U.S. military
archives and interviewing veterans across the United States.
</P>
<P>
Six veterans of the 1st Cavalry Division said they fired on the
refugee throng near No Gun Ri, and six others said they witnessed
the mass killing at the South Korean hamlet. More said they knew
or heard about it.
</P>
<P>
Armed with new evidence that former U.S. soldiers had confirmed
much of their account, the Korean claimants called for a U.S.
investigation into the killings.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the U.S. government will meet our demands and console
the wandering souls of those who died an unfair death," the
claimants said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. military has said repeatedly it found no basis for the
allegations. On Wednesday, after the AP report was released,
Pentagon spokesman P.J. Crowley said, "We just have no information
in historical files to lend any clarity to what might have
happened in July 1950." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
