<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Official Outraged by Violence of Kosovo Albanians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton's National Security Adviser Sandy Berger Thursday
expressed his outrage over the violent acts of the ethnic
Albanians against Serbs in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Berger told a gathering at the U.S. Institute of Peace that
NATO did not fight in Kosovo for one ethnic group over another.
</P>
<P>
The ethnic Albanians in Kosovo set the Serb houses on flames,
beat the Serbs and drove them out of home after NATO-led
multinational forces took control of the province in June.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that situation in the province has improved a
lot. "All in all, we are on track in rebuilding the physical
structure and in building political structures."
</P>
<P>
Since the end of the war in Kosovo, over 800,000 Kosovo
Albanian refugees have returned to the province while another
100,000 who were internally displaced have gone back to their
homes.
</P>
<P>
The energy sector and hospitals and clinics have been
revitalized and mail service has been resumed, Berger said.
</P>
</TEXT>
