<HEADLINE> Romania Benefits From Biggest EU Finance for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Starting in the year 2000,
Romania is the country that has obtained most EU funds for
regional development programs, of all the candidates to European
Union membership, said Simon Mordue, coordinator of the Phare-EU
delegation to Romania, in an interview with the local daily
Romania Libera on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mordue said that in August 1999 the largest offer for regional
development was issued for Romania, at 20 million euros. Romania
will contribute 25 percent to this budget, while the rest 75
percent will be funded by the EU. The money is going to be used
for training, retraining and job creation, as areas in which
''non-governmental organizations (NGO) have a worthy experience,''
according to Mordue.
</P>
<P>
He added that the NGO's must ''become involved effectively'' in
the implementation of another program - RICOP - intended to deal
with the consequences of restructuring and reinsertion of the
unemployed; the RICOP program is estimated at around 100 million
euros.
</P>
<P>
The EU Delegation to Romania manages directly such programs
as Phare for Partnership, aimed at financing partnerships between
NGO's or between the NGO's and other society authorities; Phare
for Democracy, which has among its top priorities the development
of the NGO's activity; Phare Lien, which fosters links between the
NGO's dealing with projects for the deprived people. All the above
mentioned programs are currently under way. 
</P>
</TEXT>
