<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Assesses Situation of Displaced People in Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The Office for the
Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs reported Thursday that there
have been large population displacements in Burundi following
intensified attacks by rebel groups around Bujumbura Rural
province.
</P>
<P>
U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard told a press conference here
Thursday that some 260,000 people are believed to have been forced
by the attacks during the past two weeks into 30 protection sites
in the area.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the total number of internally displaced persons
in the province is now estimated at 318,000 -- three quarters of
the province's population, he said, adding that the total number
of the displaced in Burundi is estimated at 807,000.
</P>
<P>
In response to this development, U.N. agencies and their
partners sent two rapid assessment teams to visit several of the
protection sites on September 27-28.
</P>
<P>
Two additional teams are scheduled to assess conditions at more
sites Friday, Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
"The team's primary findings reveal that the most urgent needs
are for access to safe water and non-food items, particularly
blankets and plastic sheeting," he said. "International
humanitarian organizations have begun to deliver safe water and
some non-food items to affected populations."
</P>
<P>
Since Tutsi paratroopers assassinated the country's first
democratically elected president, a Hutu, in 1993, more than
200,000 people, mainly Hutu civilians, have been killed in the
fighting between the Tutsi-dominated army and Hutu rebels.
</P>
<P>
Burundi's Hutus make up a majority of the country's population,
but Tutsi control the military, judiciary and much of the economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican President Expresses Worry about Oaxaca Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Mexican President Ernesto
Zedillo expressed Thursday his worry about the situation after a
strong earthquake, which has killed at least 10.
</P>
<P>
"I am very concerned about Oaxaca", Zedillo told television
media when returning to Mexico's capital from Queretaro state,
where he interrupted a working tour upon being told of the quake,
which happened at 11:31 local time (16:31 GMT).
</P>
<P>
At least 10 people dead and 35 were injured so far on Thursday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The quake had a preliminary magnitude of 7.5 and was centered
in Punta Maldonado, north of Port Angel, some 850 kilometers east
from Mexico City, the U.S. Geological Survey in Golden, Colorado
said.
</P>
<P>
Emergency organizations mentioned the existence of one dead in
Mexico's capital city and another in Veracruz state.
</P>
<P>
Oaxaca's governor Jose Murat called Televisa TV network to
report about the situation in this state, where at least eight
persons died due to the earthquake, whose epicenter lay in coastal
areas of the same state.
</P>
<P>
Mexico City, one of the world's largest cities with nearly 20
million residents in the metropolitan area, suffered a major quake
on September 19, 1985, when an 8.1-magnitude quake struck, killing
at least 9,500 people.
</P>
<P>
The recent strong earthquake in Mexico occurred in June 15 this
year in a sparsely populated mountain area 265 kilometers
southwest of Mexico City, killing at least 17 people and injuring
nearly 200. More than 7,700 homes were damaged or destroyed,
mostly in Oaxaca and Puebla states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
