<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 50th PRC Anniversary Congratulated in Berlin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, September 30 (Xinhua) -- On the eve of the 50th
birthday of the People's Republic of China, the Chinese embassy in
Berlin invited more than 800 people to its reception Thursday with
traditional Chinese music and the message that German Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder would formally visit China.
</P>
<P>
At the well-known Intercontinental Hotel in downtown Berlin,
former Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel and other prominent people in
Germany's political life were invited to the reception, at which a
traditional Chinese orchestra from Beijing played traditional
Chinese music.
</P>
<P>
The reception began with an address by Chinese Ambassador Lu
Qiutian, who eulogized the great progress of China and announced
that German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder would pay an official
visit to China next month.
</P>
<P>
"Fifty years ago, on October 1, Mao Zedong announced the birth
of the People's Republic of China and a new chapter of the Chinese
history began," said Lu.
</P>
<P>
"In these 50 years, the Chinese people have, under the
leadership of their government, made great progress both in the
domestic and foreign areas," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Especially since the beginning of our reform era, the living
quality of the Chinese people has been much bettered, and the
modernization has been propelled in all fields, and China has
become an important factor for the peace and progress of the
world," he said.
</P>
<P>
Lu praised the Sino-German relationship, saying, "There are
more cooperation and exchanges between China and Germany in the
fields of politics, economy and culture. The friendly relationship
between China and Germany is in the interests of the people in
both countries."
</P>
<P>
At the end of his speech, Lu said that German Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder would officially visit China next month. It
would be the first formal visit to China by Schroeder since he was
elected federal chancellor a year ago, he added.
</P>
<P>
The trip, he said, was expected to upgrade the Sino-German
bilateral friendship and cooperation to a more satisfying level.
</P>
</TEXT>
