<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Hostage Harmed in Myanmar Embassy in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 1 (Xinhua) -- All the hostages taken in
Myanmar embassy in Thailand were unharmed, Chatchawal Suksumjit,
spokesman of Royal Thai Police, told Xinhua Friday.
</P>
<P>
A dozen armed men stormed the Myanmar embassy in Bangkok at
Friday noon and took about 20 people hostage, including diplomats
and foreigners.
</P>
<P>
The men, armed with grenades and assault rifles, opened fire
several times with guns into the ceilings, but no hostage was
harmed.
</P>
<P>
The foreigners held included three Frenchmen, three Canadians,
one German, an American and several Malaysians, Singaporeans and
Thais.
</P>
<P>
A faxed statement from a group claiming responsibility for the
action demanded Myanmar's government free political prisoners,
enter a dialogue with the opposition and convene a democratic
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai told reporters that he was
following the situation closely and had ordered agencies concerned
to protect Myanmar embassy. He promised Thai government will try
its best to help solve the issue as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Thai Interior Minister Sanan Kachornprasart directed security
operations from the scene. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
