<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military Parade Held in Cyprus to Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The annual Independence Day
military parade was held Friday in Cyprus to mark the island's
39th anniversary of independence from British colonial rule.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides, Greek Defense Minister Akis
Tsochatzopoulos, who arrived here Thursday on a four-day official
visit, and other Cyprus government officials were present to
review the parade.
</P>
<P>
Weapons displayed in the parade included Aspide missiles,
recently acquired Russian TOR-M1 anti-aircraft systems, AMX 30B2
and T-80 tanks, armored personnel carriers and missiles launchers.
</P>
<P>
The TOR-M1 missiles, which can hit two targets at the same time,
have a maximum range of 12 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus ordered the medium-range missiles from Russia after it
gave up the deployment of Russian-made S-300 long-range missiles
under international pressure and Turkish threats of preemptive
military actions.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Cyprus reached an agreement in November, 1993 that
Greece will offers Cyprus land, sea and air cover in the event of
fresh Turkish attacks.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
After the parade, Cyprus Defense Minister Socrates Hasikos told
the press that as long as the occupation forces are here, Cyprus
has an obligation to strengthen its defense. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
