<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at GMT 1600, October 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Information Sheet said that three gunmen armed with AK-47
rifles came into the Myanmar embassy in Bangkok and held the
embassy staff as hostages at 10:50 a.m. Friday. (Myanmar-Embassy-
Hostage)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Nine members of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (
PKK) were killed in government's recent military operations in
southeastern Turkey, an official statement said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The statement, issued by the office of the Emergency Rule
Region, said that the Turkish security forces had killed nine PKK
militants in different areas of Van province. (Turkey-PKK)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GENEVA -- The accident which occurred on September 30 at a
nuclear fuel fabrication plant in Tokai-mura, Japan, is not a
public health concern outside Japanese territory and is unlikely
to have any public health impact beyond the local population, said
the World Health Organization (WHO) Friday.
</P>
<P>
Known technically as a criticality event, the accident involved
the unscheduled fissioning of uranium 235, according to WHO. This
led to the generation of a strong external radiation field
comprising neutrons and gamma-rays and the release of radioactive
materials in the form of fission products which have been detected
off site. (WHO-Japan-Leakage)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- All the hostages taken in Myanmar embassy in
Thailand were unharmed, Chatchawal Suksumjit, spokesman of Royal
Thai Police, told Xinhua Friday.
</P>
<P>
A dozen armed men stormed the Myanmar embassy in Bangkok at
Friday noon and took about 20 people hostage, including diplomats
and foreigners.
</P>
<P>
The men, armed with grenades and assault rifles, opened fire
several times with guns into the ceilings, but no hostage was
harmed. (Thailand-Myanmar-Hostage) 
</P>
</TEXT>
