<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Marks 50th Founding Anniversary of PRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Fireworks display, carnivals,
parade and performances have turned Hong Kong into a sea of
jubilation Friday on the occasion of 50th anniversary of the
founding of the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
As early as 8:00 in the morning, the national flag-raising
ceremony started the prelude of the celebrations in the two-year-
old Special Administrative Region (SAR) of China.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Hong Kong residents held miniature versions of the
Chinese national flag and the HKSAR flag in their hands, and
cheered as the five-starred national flag was hoisted into the air.
</P>
<P>
Though several thousand miles away from China's capital Beijing,
Hong Kong is filled with the same festival atmosphere. The local
residents are excited to share the pride with all the Chinese
people on the meaningful day.
</P>
<P>
The live broadcast of the grand celebration at the Tiananmen
Square became the spotlight in the morning. The large screen at
the downtown Times Square attracted thousands of pedestrians, many
of whom took out their cameras to record the historic picture.
</P>
<P>
To commemorate the event, Hong Kong Post issued a set of
special stamps on China's Golden Jubilee, and the stamps became
good buy for the enthusiastic stamp collectors.
</P>
<P>
Residents of the New Territories were treated to recreational
activities and entertainment programs rich in traditional Chinese
culture during the National Day celebrations organized by the
Provisional Regional Council.
</P>
<P>
"Through these programs, we hope to strengthen public
understanding of traditional culture and enhance their sense of
belonging to the motherland," said Tony Kan, vice-chairman of the
Provisional Regional Council, at the opening ceremony of the Dance
Carnival.
</P>
<P>
The National Day Recreation and Sports Carnival organized by
the Provisional Urban Council at Victoria Park Friday was well-
received by 35,000 participants as they enjoyed the holiday with
fun and laughter.
</P>
<P>
First staged in 1997, the carnival attracted thousands of
people of all ages to participate each year at Victoria Park to
celebrate the meaning day.
</P>
<P>
The highlight of the event was the performance by a thousand
Tai Chi players who put their efforts together to form the
numerical figure "50" at the central lawn of the park.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the "Sport-for-All Spectacular" variety show,
produced in conjunction with Hit Radio 997 featuring stage
performances by local popular singers, dancers, cartoon characters,
clowns and magicians, had added color to the event.
</P>
<P>
Members of the public had also participated in sessions of
popular recreation and sports activities such as basketball,
cycling, fitness exercise and table-tennis to share the fun and
excitement of these sports activities.
</P>
<P>
Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of the HKSAR, attended the
evening gala with some forty thousand people at Hong Kong Stadium
as soon as he returned Hong Kong from Beijing Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Military drills performance by more than 600 members of the
Hong Kong Garrison of the People's Liberation Army won warm
response from the local residents.
</P>
<P>
The finale of the celebration show, called "Joy to the New
Millennium", comprised a grand musical cum dance show performed by
youth groups, featuring some of the best known local pop singers.
They were backed up by marches of uniformed youth groups, as well
as lion and dragon dances.
</P>
<P>
Echoing Beijing's celebrations, a splendid fireworks display
was launched in the sky of Victoria Harbor of Hong Kong in the
evening.
</P>
<P>
The glamour of some fireworks sustained for 12 seconds after
explosion and formed five layers of multi-color waterfalls. The
grand finale entitled "Millennium Starlight" was the climax of the
night.
</P>
<P>
An orchestrated fireworks brighten up the entire Victoria
Harbor to symbolize Hong Kong's bright future in the new
millennium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
