<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Opposition Warned Not to Resort to Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Opposition
parties were warned Friday not to resort to violence and disrupt
public order especially with the general election which is
believed not far away.
</P>
<P>
Issuing the warning, Deputy Home Minister Azmi Khalid said that
otherwise the government will take action against them.
</P>
<P>
The government does not want peace in the country to be
jeopardized because it had helped the country to gain the
confidence of foreign investors and intensified economic
development, he said in Taiping, some 290 kilometers north of
here, according to Bernama news agency.
</P>
<P>
Azmi said the opposition parties were given the opportunity to
hold ceramahs (lectures) and provide public access to their
newspapers and various information posted over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
But, the opposition parties lacked issues that they resorted to
disturbing ceramahs of the ruling United Malays National
Organization (UMNO) by making noises, he said.
</P>
<P>
"They seemed to be desperate and it is not surprising if they
resort to violence as the general election approaches," he was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The deputy home minister said the opposition should realize
that the best way to change the government is through the ballot
boxes and not resorting to violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
