<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Taliban Offensive in North Repulses: Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Afghan opposition alliance
Friday claimed to have repulsed a Taliban offensive at Khanabad in
northern Afghanistan after an fierce three-hour battle early this
morning, news reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban launched the attack on the strategic town in
northern province of Kunduz with some 1,000 troops, supported by
heavy artillery shelling and air bombards, opposition spokesman
Mohammad Habeel said.
</P>
<P>
However, the attack was repelled by the opposition forces after
three hours of fighting when 35 Taliban troops were killed,
claimed the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
There was no immediate confirmation from independent sources on
the opposition claims.
</P>
<P>
Khanabad is located on the main highway heading eastward to
Taloqan, capital of neighboring Takhar province, of which the two
warring sides have been locked in a fighting for the control.
</P>
</TEXT>
