<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 100,000 Chinese Celebrate PRC's 50th Birthday at Evening Gala </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- A total of 100,000 people held a
grand soiree on Tiananmen Square this evening celebrating the 50th
founding anniversary of the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
Splendid fireworks rocketed into the sky over the square as Jia
Qinglin, secretary of the Beijing Committee of the Chinese
Communist Party, declared the opening of the event from the
Tian'anmen Rostrum at 8 o'clock.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin and other top Party and state
leaders shared the jubilant occasion with the 100,000 participants
who came from all ethnic groups across China.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of lights, colorful fountains, and fireworks lit up
the world's largest square with a floor space of 450,000 square
meters.
</P>
<P>
A central performance area between Tian'anmen Square and the
Rostrum was set aside for more than 10,000 performers, and the
square was divided into eight sections in which 80,000 people
danced in groups.
</P>
<P>
A lion dance performed by over 100 farmers from Lanzhou,
capital of northwest China's Gansu Province, kicked off the
entertainment in front of the Rostrum. Then dancers carrying waist
drums, hand drums, flower drums, Taiping (Peace) drums and others
staged deafening drum dances.
</P>
<P>
Performers from many regions across the country did folk dances
with lanterns in the shapes of lotuses, wheels, dragons and
pavilions.
</P>
<P>
Following the traditional performance, 100 pairs of ballroom
dancers, a first for the country's National Day gala, performed
tango sand waltzes, followed by girls and boys who presented
enthusiastic modern dances.
</P>
<P>
Forty-two-year-old Ye Guang, an official in charge of public
relations work for the gala, said, "I witnessed our country's
remarkable development over the past decades. And the grand soiree
tonight displays the prosperity and power of China, as well as
people's peaceful and joyful lives."
</P>
<P>
Some 80,000 people on the square danced to the rhythm of "Good
Luck to You, Motherland."
</P>
<P>
Sun Wei, a 21-year-old student from the Beijing Institute of
Electronic Engineering, said he was envied by friends and
relatives for having the opportunity to dance here tonight.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 180 kinds of fireworks burst into the air, 50 to 300
meters high over the square, during the two-hour gala. Many kinds
of magnificent fireworks were seen in Beijing for the first time
tonight.
</P>
<P>
More than 300 performers in the traditional costumes of China's
56 ethnic groups danced in the central area, followed by a huge
float in the shape of a peony flower. When the flower blossomed,
three singers representing China's old, middle-aged and young
people appeared and sang the theme song of the celebration, "Good
Luck to You, Motherland".
</P>
<P>
Bright and colorful fireworks were sent into air for the last
time tonight, while the song of "Singing in Praise of the
Motherland" by all 100,000 participants resounded through the air.
The evening gala concluded amid thunderous and jubilant cheers and
applause. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
