<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kongers Entertained with Grand Gala of National Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 1 (Xinhua) -- A grand gala was eye-catching
for tens of thousands of Hong Kong people Friday afternoon at Hong
Kong Stadium.
</P>
<P>
The celebration show marking the 50th anniversary of the
founding of the People's Republic of China was the largest of its
kind ever staged in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Forty thousand people were treated to a two-hour extravaganza
featuring some unique performances to celebrate the Golden Jubilee,
which began at 5:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
The Chief Executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region Tung Chee Hwa attended the gala as soon as he returned Hong
Kong from Beijing this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Tung and the Hong Kong delegation led by him took part in
various celebration activities in the capital of China, including
the reception of National Day Thursday evening and the military
parade at the Tien'anmen Square this morning.
</P>
<P>
"It is a great honor for the HKSAR government to host this
celebration today together with the community to commemorate the
50 anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic of China,"
Tung said when he delivered a speech at the gala.
</P>
<P>
After 50 years of sustained efforts, China is moving towards a
future of steady development, prosperity and peace, he said. The
international status of China has been enhanced with rapid
progress in economics, technology and national defense being
achieved, he added.
</P>
<P>
"We have implemented fully the policies 'One Country, Two
System', Hong Kong people administering Hong Kong and a high
degree of autonomy," he said, stressing that Hong Kong has been
very fortunate to return to the motherland when she is growing
stronger and gaining in stature.
</P>
<P>
"As a member of the Chinese people, no matter where we are, we
should strive to contribute selflessly to the growth of the nation,
" Tung said.
</P>
<P>
Highlight of the evening was undoubtedly military drills by
more than 600 members of the Hong Kong Garrison of the People's
Liberation Army on an unprecedented scale outside the mainland.
</P>
<P>
On show was bayonet group calisthenics which focused on the
soldiers' bearings, discipline and coordinated movements; the
wushu group calisthenics showing their martial art skills; and a
military band tracing out calisthenics patterns in time with music.
</P>
<P>
The disciplined performances won waves of warm applause from
joyful, enthusiastic spectators, many of whom carried with them a
telescope or a camera, trying to get a closer view and to preserve
the photos for a lasting memory.
</P>
<P>
"I has never seen a performance like this. Their appearance and
bearing, their discipline and their coordinated movement stunned
me," said Lam, a 67-year-old local resident.
</P>
<P>
"Paying too much attention to the performance, I nearly forgot
to cover the news," said a young female reporter for a Hong Kong-
based Mexican television company.
</P>
<P>
Local items included a dance team comprising 500 young students
drawn from the Hong Kong Dance Federation from 12 secondary
schools.
</P>
<P>
The gala also represented a unique musical entitled "Dance of
Youth", which incorporated traditional characteristics of Oriental
and Western dance as well as social features unique to Hong Kong.
This is the first musical offerings of its kind originating in the
Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Wushu Union team made a huge dragon and four
smaller ones plus 50 lions come to life. The performance entitled
"Show of Vim and Vigor" comprised one big dragon and four small
ones to form the number "50", symbolizing the resourcefulness of
the Hong Kong community joining in the celebration.
</P>
<P>
The finale of the celebration show, called "Joy to the New
Millennium", comprised a grand musical cum dance show performed by
youth groups, featuring some of the best known local pop singers.
They were backed up by marches of uniformed youth groups, as well
as lion and dragon dances.
</P>
<P>
Over 2,500 youths presented a flip board display showing the
SAR emblem and event logo of the 50th anniversary of the National
Day, marking the passion of Hong Kong people rejoicing in this
special occasion with blessing on the prosperous and promising
future of the country into the new millennium.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Has Been Fortunate: Tung Chee Hwa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) said here
Friday that Hong Kong has been very fortunate to return to the
motherland when she is growing stronger and gaining in stature.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark here in Hong Kong Friday evening while
speaking to the more than 40,000 spectators at the Hong Kong
Stadium where a grand show was held to celebrate the 50th
anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
"Since the establishment of the HKSAR over two years ago, with
the collective effort of Hong Kong people and the total support of
the Central People's Government, we have implemented fully the
policies 'One Country, Two Systems', Hong Kong people
administering Hong Kong and a high degree of autonomy. Under the '
Basic Law', the social, economic and legal systems of Hong Kong
have been maintained; our lifestyle has been preserved; Hong Kong
people continue to enjoy the freedoms of speech, of the press and
of assembly. These rights are fully protected," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But we will not be complacent with these achievements. We
still have to apply ourselves fully to create more wealth and to
turn this into a better quality of life and environment for our
community." he added.
</P>
<P>
"In the last two years, Hong Kong people have suffered
economically due to the Asian financial crisis. But we have faced
and overcome these challenges in a positive spirit; we have
maintained Hong Kong's vitality, restored our confidence and
resolve. We have gone past the most difficult period for the Hong
Kong economy, and I believe that better times lie ahead," he
declared.
</P>
<P>
Tung flew to Beijing Thursday and reviewed the grand National
Day parade at Tiananmen Square Friday morning and returned to Hong
Kong in the afternoon to attend celebration activities here in
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Reflecting what he felt, he said: "This afternoon, while I was
returning to Hong Kong, I surveyed the vista of our vast country.
It was a moving sight. I know that across this vast land 56 ethnic
groups, 1.2 billion people are living in peace, mastering the
opportunity of a century to create a civilized and abundant
society, and realizing the ideals of a great nation."
</P>
<P>
"As a member of the Chinese people, no matter where we are, we
should strive to contribute selflessly to the growth of the nation,
" he pledged.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
