<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Wins Team Event in World Rhythmic Gymnastics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Russia won the team event for a
gold medal Friday night in the 23rd Rhythmic Gymnastics World
Championships in Osaka, Japan.
</P>
<P>
Belarus came in second and the Ukrainians was third among the
four top teams competing in the final round. Germany placed fourth.
</P>
<P>
The Russians with Alina Kabaeva performing with the hoop and
the ribbon, and Youlia Barsoukova dancing with the ball and the
rope scored a total of 119.089 points.Belarus' Yulia Raskina, with
the ball and the rope, and Valeria Vatkina, with the other two
kinds of apparatus, combined for 118.656 points.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainians with Olympic bronze medalist Elena Vitrichenko
dancing with the rope and the ball, and Anna Bessonova with the
hoop and Tamara Yerofeeva with the ribbon, tallied 118.322 points.
For Germany, Monique Strobl performed all the four requirements in
the final round, collecting a total of 116.550 points.
</P>
<P>
In this sport for women, gymnasts dance to music, using balls,
ropes, ribbons, hoops or clubs. Acrobatics is permitted, but not
tumbling. The team event Friday was the first of seven finals in
the five-day competition that began on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The world championships, the first of its kind ever staged in
Asia since the International Gymnastics Federation (FIG) was
founded in 1981, also serve as a qualifying event for the Sydney
Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
The FIG on Friday announced 19 of 24 individual berths for the
Olympics next year, based on the results in the preliminary round
of the team competition held Wednesday and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The berths included two each from Russia, Ukraine, Belarus,
Germany and Spain, and one each from France, Bulgaria, Japan,
Greece, Israel, Italy, Poland, Hungary and Finland. The remaining
five berths will include one each from Africa, the American
continent, Asia, Europe and Oceania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
