<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Faces Water Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Like elsewhere in the world,
water crisis will loom large in Nepal in the 21st century, if the
government fails to formulate effective plans and policies, The
Kathmandu Post quoted experts as saying Friday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at an interaction program organized by Nepal Forum for
Environment Journalists here Thursday, the experts called on the
government to formulate an effective policy to ensure supply of
safe drinking water.
</P>
<P>
Nepal is rich in water resources. But utilization is low
because of poor government management and lack of money to develop
the resources. The country as a whole has not yet faced serious
drinking water shortage problem, but the Kathmandu Valley has been
hit for several years.
</P>
<P>
In Kathmandu, the average daily demand is 150 million liters
and the supply is 120 million liters in the wet season and 70
million liters in the dry season, according to an official from
the Nepal Water Supply Corporation.
</P>
<P>
According to Ministry of Housing and Physical Planning, access
to safe water in Nepal is 67 percent, compared with 82 percent in
South Asia.
</P>
<P>
In the whole world, some 1.2 billion people lack access to safe
water and the figure will increase to 2.3 billion by 2025 unless
action is stepped up, according to a press release issued by the
program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
