<HEADLINE> Nyerere In Critical Condition, But Still Conscious </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Daughter of former Tanzanian
President Julius Nyerere said on Friday that her father was
critically ill with leukemia in a British hospital but denied
Tanzanian government reports that he was in a coma.
</P>
<P>
"His condition is critical but he is not in a coma," a Reuters
report quoted Anna Nyerere as saying here.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere was still able to utter a few words to family gathered
at his bedside, she said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a Tanzanian government spokesman said that Nyerere had
slipped into a coma after a sudden relapse on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
She said the former president, 77, was in intensive care at St
Thomas's hospital in London.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere, who was admitted to hospital last Friday, is a major
figure in post-colonial Africa.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere, who led his country to independence from Britain in
1961, became president in 1962 and ruled until stepping down in
1985.
</P>
<P>
Since then he has continued to play an advisory role in
Tanzanian and African affairs, most recently leading regional
efforts to bring peace to Burundi.
</P>
<P>
He was diagnosed with chronic leukemia in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
