<HEADLINE> No Agreement on Safe Passage: Palestinian Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian Minister for Civil
Affairs Jamil Tarif on Friday denied the signing of an agreement
with Israel on the opening of a safe passage route on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Tarif said the joint Palestinian-Israeli committee had failed,
after several hours of talks until dawn Friday, to reach any
agreement on the opening of the southern safe passage route that
links Gaza strip and Tarkumia near the West Bank city of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
He said that differences between the two sides mainly concern
the free travelling for Palestinians, and the safe passage card.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli side demands that Israeli military has the right to
arrest suspected Palestinians travelling along the route, a stance
adamantly rejected by the Palestinian side.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, the Palestinian side rejected the Israeli position
that Palestinian citizens should obtain the safe passage card from
the Israeli liaison offices, asserting that the Palestinian
National Authority is solely responsible for the matter.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said on Thursday that the
safe passage route would be opened on Sunday, in implementation of
the Sharm el-Sheikh Memorandum.
</P>
<P>
Tarif pointed out that the Israeli government would have to
bear the responsibility of postponing the opening of the safe
passage route. 
</P>
</TEXT>
