<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dances at PRC Anniversary Evening Gala </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- About 100,000 people from all
walks of life, and dancers from all 56 ethnic groups nationwide
gathered together at Tian'anmen Square this evening performing
colorful dances during the grand gala celebrating the 50th
anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic of China (PRC)
.
</P>
<P>
With delightful melodies featuring best wishes for the
motherland, patriotism, expectations for a new century and a happy
life, people of every stripe staged a dozen mass dances of
diversified ethnic groups including the Han, Mongolian, Uygur, and
Tibetan.
</P>
<P>
Among the dances, the "Ode to the Motherland" specially
emphasizes unity and common progress for all ethnic groups in
China, said Zhao Dongming, an official in charge of the evening
gala.
</P>
<P>
It combines the unique dancing art of different ethnic groups,
and expressed their common regard for National Day, Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
Dances featuring various kinds of drums also appeared in the
processionals passing along the square. These drum dances are
popular from Gansu Province in northwest China to Jiangsu Province
in east China, and from Tibet in southwest China to Henan Province
in central China.
</P>
<P>
Performers from many regions across the country staged folk
dances with lanterns in the shape of lotus, wheel, dragon and
pavilion.
</P>
<P>
The parade passing the square also included a phoenix and
dragon dance echoing the huge dragon float of the morning's parade,
and the blooming peonies on the peony float symbolizes peace and
stability for China and its people.
</P>
<P>
Following the phoenix and dragon dance, one hundred pairs of
ballroom dancers, a first for the country's National Day gala,
performed tangos, waltzes, ballets and Chinese dances.
</P>
<P>
At the rear of the parade, hundreds of dancers in lame costumes
performed modern dances with enthusiasm and earnest greetings for
the motherland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
