<HEADLINE> Eastern China's Tide-Watching Festival Closes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The '99 International Tide-
Watching Festival on the Qiantang River ended today in the city of
Haining in east China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
As many as 700,000 domestic and overseas visitors were
attracted by the event which included kite-flying shows, art
performances, evening galas, fireworks and sightseeing tours.
</P>
<P>
The tide of the Qiantang River near Haining is one of China's
most amazing sights. This year Haining built up a 5.5-km-long road
for tide watchers along with other facilities such as lavatories
and viewing platforms.
</P>
<P>
The festival has been held annually since 1994 and has
attracted more than five millions tourists to Haining on the
northern bank of the river, and to Xiaoshan on the southern bank.
</P>
<P>
Tide-watching on the river has become an increasingly important
part of the local tourism industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
