<HEADLINE> Guests Hail National Day Celebrations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Today's celebration activities
to mark the 50th birthday of new China were well designed and they
reflected China's tremendous successes in the past 50 years,
representatives of various walks of life of China and overseas
friends who were invited to watch them at the reviewing stands
said in interviews with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
More than 25,000 invited guests, including 5,000 from overseas,
watched the military and civilian parade on visitors' stands on
both sides of the Tian'anmen Rostrum.
</P>
<P>
Wei Qing, an officer from the Nanjing military area command,
said the high-tech weapons shown in the military parade
illustrated China's big strides in its military modernization
drive.
</P>
<P>
Yong Sionghai, a Brunei businessman, said the parade and rally
were very encouraging to overseas Chinese, adding that "the future
belongs to the Chinese."
</P>
<P>
A middle-aged couple from the Boeing Company of the United
States said that the military and civilian parade are very
splendid. They have been impressed by the children who released
the colorful balloons and surged forward to the Gold Water Bridge.
</P>
<P>
Viktor Hanuska from France, the Beijing representative of the
Michelin Asia (HK) Ltd., said the military parade is of a very
large scale, comparable with the several parades he saw in France.
The parade was very-well organized and the tanks and armored
vehicles kept their formations very accurately.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Suchu, daughter of noted former Kuomintang general Zhang
Zhizhong, said she felt very proud of the women soldiers and
militia, who are the pride of all Chinese women.
</P>
<P>
Wang Quji, 67, who attended the parade marking the founding of
new China in 1949 as a high school student, said, "I felt very
excited and encouraged. The parade is a proof of China's strength
and prosperity."
</P>
<P>
Jackson Leung S.M., a Hong Kong member of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC), said he felt honored to
witness the grand ceremony as a representative of the Hong Kong
compatriots two years later after the territory returned to China.
</P>
<P>
Willian Ho, managing director of the Macao-based P&AMP;W Money
Changer Ltd., said Macao compatriots are very proud to see their
motherland gets stronger and stronger, and that it is especially
exciting for them at this moment as Macao is to return to the
motherland soon.
</P>
<P>
Hong Xia, a model teacher from Inner Mongolia said that the
fact she and representatives of other ethnic groups have been
invited to watch the celebrations shows the government care about
the ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
Lee Hong Pe, an overseas Chinese from Myanmar, said he would
write some poems in Chinese to remember the precious moment for
good.  
