<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rich, New Fireworks for PRC Anniversary Evening Gala </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- About 200 kinds of fireworks
will be set off into the sky over Tian'anmen Square in four
segments during the grand gala celebrating the 50th anniversary of
the founding of the People's Republic of China (PRC) this evening.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 types of fireworks were specially developed for
today's evening gala. The fireworks will be set off from 11 sites
during the evening, including one site at Tian'anmen Square.
</P>
<P>
They include time-honored traditional Chinese fireworks brands,
internationally popular fireworks imported from foreign countries,
and newly developed products. The fireworks will demonstrate such
features as greater brightness of colors, lasting longer in the
sky, spreading to a greater extent, and simultaneously changing
color as they are set off.
</P>
<P>
The fireworks range from three inches to 16 inches long, and
will be set off from the height of 200 to 400 meters, with the
diameter of the explosion reaching up to 200 meters, producing a
great number of beautiful scenes in Beijing's evening sky.
</P>
<P>
The ignition of this year's fireworks will be carried out in
carefully planned groups in order to express specially designed
themes, and produce a clear-cut intensity.
</P>
<P>
For instance, after the fireworks called "The Star of Macao" is
set off, a golden cocoa tree symbolizing Macao will change color
from gold to red, which is favored by Chinese as a sign of good
luck, and celebrates happy occasions such as the return of Macao
to China on December 20.
</P>
<P>
Fireworks with music, which has been developed by China for the
first time, will also be set off at this evening's gala. The music
selected for this is titled "Marching Toward the New Era" and this
segment of the pyrotechnics will last four minutes and two seconds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao to Return to China 80 Days after Nation's 50th Birthday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- When the fireworks lit up the
night sky and the faces of those celebrating the nation's 50th
birthday in Tian'anmen Square, a huge digital countdown clock on
the east side of the square showed that Macao will return to the
embrace of the motherland in 80 days.
</P>
<P>
Chinese call 1999 a year of double happiness: the people's
republic's 50th anniversary and Macao's return to the motherland.
And each of the hundreds of thousands of people in Tian'anmen
Square tonight could not help but turn their eyes toward the
countdown clock.
</P>
<P>
When the clock was erected on May 5 last year, Ho Hau Wah, at
the time vice-chairman of the Preparatory Committee for the Macao
Special Administrative Region (SAR), said the countdown clock not
only reminds the public of the time Macao will return to the
motherland, December 20, 1999, but also urges us to expedite the
preparatory work for the establishment of the Macao SAR.
</P>
<P>
Ho, who has been elected as the first chief executive of the
Macao SAR, came to participate in the celebration today and said
the preparatory work for establishing the Macao SAR is well under
way.
</P>
<P>
A large exhibition on the history of Macao opened several days
ago in the Museum of Chinese History behind the countdown clock.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Na, dressed in splendid attire and dancing in Tian'anmen
Square tonight, visited the exhibition several days ago. "I'm
looking forward to Macao's return to China," she said.
</P>
<P>
Zhang, who works for the Chongwen District government in
Beijing, said she took part in a contest on knowledge of Macao and
got to know a middle school student in Macao.
</P>
<P>
"We wrote letters to each other and decided to visit the
Tian'anmen Rostrum, the Palace Museum, and the Great Wall together
after the return of Macao," she said.
</P>
<P>
Li Xiang, a sophomore from the Beijing Business School, waved
his school flag with all his might in front of the countdown clock.
</P>
<P>
"My classmates and I watched the grand parade on TV this
morning and we feel that our country is becoming strong and
prosperous. The history of infringing on Chinese territory and
sovereignty by others has gone forever," said the 20-year-old
student. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
