<HEADLINE> Feature: Overseas Guests Attend China's National Day Celebrations ( 1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Kan Yuesai cast her image in the
hearts of millions of Chinese in 1984 as an anchorperson of the
PBS of the United States which helped China televise live the
celebrations marking the 35th anniversary of the founding of new
China on October 1 of that year.
</P>
<P>
Today, however, she came to Tian'anmen Square again but as a
viewer on the visitors' stands adjacent the Tian'anmen Rostrum.
</P>
<P>
"China no longer needs foreign newsmen's help. She has her own
communications satellite," she said. "Ping! The signal goes around
worldwide," she added.
</P>
<P>
She said that there have been great changes over the past 15
years, which have transformed China into a mighty country, and the
nation is able to see its future clearly.
</P>
<P>
Like Kan, some 6,000 overseas people, and representatives of
the compatriots in Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan, have watched
today's grand celebrations marking the 50th anniversary of the
founding of the People's Republic of China, together with 500,000
elated Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
Some of them arrived at the visitors' stands two hours ahead of
the beginning of the celebrations scheduled at 10:00 this morning.
Wearing badges of China's national emblem, lots of them were
waving China's miniature national flags. They applaused warmly
while enjoying the colorful procession.
</P>
<P>
What they were interested in most was the military parade, the
largest and the most advanced to show China's latest weapons.
</P>
<P>
"I am intrested in the military parade. China's military force
is progressing rapidly, and it has developed some advanced
technologies," said Paul Southwell, military attache of the New
Zealand embassy in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Chong King Liong, an overseas Chinese from Malaysia, said that
the military parade was a real splendor, and all the latest
weapons displayed in the parade showed that China is becoming a
powerful country.
</P>
<P>
Abu Roshde Rokonuddawla, military attache of the Bangladeshi
embassy in Beijing, said that "a strong Chinese military force
will not constitiute any threat to the world."
</P>
</TEXT>
