<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise, Dollar Weakens in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices continued rising in
Tokyo Friday on expectations of an economic recovery in Japan.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange gained 107.10 points, or 0.61
percent, from Thursday's close to end at 17,712.56.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, added 8.25 points or 0.55 percent to 1,515.
08.
</P>
<P>
Expectations that the Bank of Japan (BOJ) quarterly Tankan
business confidence survey will show an improvement from the
previous survey encouraged investors to buy stocks, said a dealer.
</P>
<P>
The Tankan figures are to be released Monday morning before the
stock market opens.
</P>
<P>
A major nuclear accident at a uranium processing facility in
Ibaraki Prefecture on Thursday had a negative impact only on
issues relating to nuclear businesses, such as Hitachi, Toshiba
and electric power firms.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section fell to 543.52 million shares
from 559.76 million shares Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Itochu Corp. was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers outnumbered
gainers 654 to 585 despite the rises in the Nikkei index and the
TOPIX, with 101 issues ending unchanged.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo Foreign Exchange, the U.S. dollar weakened against
the yen, dipping to the 105 yen level on yen buybacks after market
players shrugged off negative effects from Thursday's nuclear
accident.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. dollar was quoted at 105.92-95 yen at 5 p.m., down
from 106.21-24 yen at 0 a.m., and from 106.35-45 yen in New York
overnight. The U.S. currency was traded at 105.64-67 yen in Tokyo
late Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
