<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Russian troops launched a major ground offensive into the
separatist southern region of Chechnya Thursday with the apparent
aim of creating a buffer zone to block infiltration of Chechen
guerrillas into the neighboring areas, according to Russian and
Chechen officials.
</P>
<P>
-- Workers accidentally set off a nuclear-fission chain
reaction at a uranium procession plant about 120 kilometers
northeast of Tokyo on Thursday morning, sending three employees to
the hospital, two of them in critical condition, and exposing an
unknown number of nearby residents to at least low levels of
radiation.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The United States and Russia have quietly resolved a dispute
over the illegal sale of IBM computers to Russia's leading nuclear
weapons lab, American officials said.
</P>
<P>
-- The CIA withdrew three officers from Germany, but American
officials played down the incident, saying it resulted from
friction with the German internal security service.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Russian banks and other firms are being investigated by tax
authorities for use of offshore accounts. Tax evasion appears to
be the primary concern.
</P>
<P>
-- Indonesia's new national assembly is to meet Friday, marking
a milestone for democracy in the post-Suharto period. Electing a
president will be its main purpose, and threatens conflict.
</P>
