<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fourth Session of Lao National Assembly Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The fourth ordinary session of the
fourth legislature of Lao National Assembly (NA) was opened in
Vientiane on Thursday, Lao official news agency KPL reported
Friday.
One of the main tasks of the session, which will last to October
15, is to adopt the state budget for fiscal year 1999-2000 and
socio-economic development plans.
</P>
<P>
In his opening speech, President of the NA Samane Viyaket urged
all NA members to make amendments to socio-economic development
plans when they are thought necessary in order to fulfill targets.
</P>
<P>
During this session NA members will receive reports on the
1998-1999 socio-economic development and hear about the
implementation of the Constitution and laws passed in the past
years.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the members of the national legislation on
implementation of the 1998-1999 social economic plan, Lao Prime
Minister Sisavath Keobounphanh said that although Laos has
achieved several of its objectives, such as political stability,
construction of the infrastructure, solidarity among people and
the extension of dry-season rice cultivation areas, it still faces
problems.
</P>
<P>
"Laos still faces some difficult situations: the economic
growth rate has slowed down; the inflation rate is still too high;
the price of goods and the exchange rate fluctuate strongly and
the standard of living among state employees and the general
public is still low," he said.
</P>
<P>
The immediate task in preparation for the 21st century,
Sisavath stressed, is to improve macroeconomic planning and
control inflation and exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
The government will intensively promote and control investments
in domestic production, infrastructure construction projects and
government priority programs.
</P>
<P>
The government will also seek to upgrade the effectiveness of
the state administrative management and improve responsibilities
and duties among state employees.
</P>
<P>
Attending the session were advisor to the Lao People's
Revolutionary Party Central Committee Nouhak Phoumsavanh,
President of the Lao PDR Khamtay Siphondone, and Prime Minister
Sisavath Keobounthanh. 
</P>
</TEXT>
