<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Parade Features China's Military Strength (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Unified strides of the paraders,
shining rifles, rumbling tanks, missiles of different sizes, and
whistling jet fighters at today's National Day military parade
were among the most spectacular scenes attracting those at
Tian'anmen Square.
</P>
<P>
The half million people attending the celebrations bursted into
thunderous applauses many times during the 40-minute parade,
marvelling at the august appearances of officers and soldiers of
the People's Liberation Army (PLA) as well as their advanced
weapons.
</P>
<P>
At about 10:30, march-past began amidst the music played by a
military band. A guard of honor in three colors: green, white and
blue, representing the PLA three services, marched before the
Tian'anmen Rostrum to solute the Party and state leaders present
on the rostrum.
</P>
<P>
It was the very honor guard that have splashed over 2,000
reception ceremonies for visiting heads of state and raised
China's national flag at the ceremony for China's resumption of
exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong about two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Following were square formations representing military
academies, led by a formation composed of cadets from the
University of National Defense, China's equivalent of West Point
of the United States.
</P>
<P>
This university has been called "cradle of generals" since most
high-ranking officers of the PLA are its graduates.
</P>
<P>
And today, a notebook computer is just as necessary as a
handgun for a cadet here. "China's new generation of generals are
trained to deal with hi-tech warfare in the future," said the head
of the formation, Lu Guangxin, in an interview before the parade.
</P>
<P>
The 17 ground formations taking part in the parade also
included those composed of Marine Corps, special armed police,
pilots, military reserves and militia. Those sun-tanned young men
and women all looked radiant and in good shape.
</P>
<P>
Of the army units marching past the Tian'anmen Rostrum, some
had the glorious and victorious history of taking part in the War
of Resistance Against Japan (1937-1945), and others were commended
for protecting people's lives and property in the fight against
the Yangtze River flood last summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
