<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Parade Features China's Military Strength (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At 10:42, 25 armored formations of more than 400 tanks,
carriers, artillery, missiles began rumbling through Tian'anmen
Square. The state-of-the-art infantry fighting vehicles, tracked
and wheeled, armored personnel carriers, drawn or self-propelled
howitzers, self-propelled guns, smoothbore guns, multiple rocket
launchers, anti-aircraft guns and cannons were sporting their
skyward barrels and scatter guns.
</P>
<P>
At sight of the tanks with only two soldiers visible and
equipped with smoothbore guns, some weaponry zealots yelled, "they
are new tanks." According to military experts, they are a new
generation of battle tanks made in China, featuring light weight,
thick shell, strong fire power and enduring viability in battle
fields. The helmets of tank soldiers indicate that the tanks are
equipped with an advanced communications system.
</P>
<P>
According to military sources, more than 90 percent of the new
weapons and equipment making their appearance in today's parade,
including rifles in the first 17 formations, were developed and
produced by China itself.
</P>
<P>
Then came the family of missiles, including surface-to-air,
ship-to-air, ship-to-ship missiles and intercontinental missiles
of the Second Artillery Corps.
</P>
<P>
Missiles on display were arranged in the order of their sizes,
from small to large as the parade proceeded, and culminated in the
12 missiles that are about 20 meters long and nearly three meters
in diameter. The appearance of the intercontinental surface-to-
surface missile phalanx attracted the VIPs on the Tian'anmen
Rostrum, the media and the rest of the half million people on the
square.
</P>
<P>
Even before the last few armored vehicles passed the Tian'anmen
Rostrum, ten echelons of 132 warplanes emerged at the east end of
the sky. Just in minutes, bombers, aerial tankers, fighters,
strike fighters, ground attack fighters skimmed over the
Tian'anmen Square. Some looked like over-sized birds, others like
swift rockets; some sweeping at the height of 800 meters,
helicopters flying just 250 meters high, with pilots silhouette
visible.
</P>
<P>
One of the most notable aircraft was a China-made strike
fighter named "Feibao," literally meaning "flying leopard."
</P>
<P>
The bulky echelons of advanced aircraft drew more waves of
applauses and cheers from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
During the 40-minute parade, over 100,000 primary and high
school pupils on the square successively formed five phrases
consisting of 20 gigantic bold Chinese characters: "politically
qualified, militarily competent, having a fine style of work,
strict discipline and adequate logistic support."
</P>
<P>
The principles, set for the PLA by President Jiang Zemin, were
also vivid depiction of the armed forces on display, according to
military observers.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the policy of building fewer but better troops, China
has been cutting down the muster roll by an average 100,000
annually since 1986 and reducing the proportion of military
expenditure to the gross national product. Analysts say that
judging from today's parade, the PLA can live up to the
expectations of the Chinese people to realize the country's
reunification and safeguard China's territorial integrity and help
to maintain regional and world peace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
