<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Holds Grand National Day Soiree </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- A grand soiree marking the 50th
anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic of China
started on the Tian'anmen Square in downtown Beijing at 8 o'clock
this evening.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin and other top Communist Party and
state leaders Li Peng, Zhu Rongji, Li Ruihuan, Hu Jintao, Wei
Jianxing and Li Lanqing are present on the Tian'anmen Rostrum
opposite to the square to share this jubilant occasion with the
100,000 soiree participants from all ethnic groups across China.
</P>
<P>
Splendid fireworks were set off to the sky over the Tian'anmen
Square as Beijing's Party Secretary Jia Qinglin declared open the
soiree from the Rostrum. At the same time, a large entertainment
show began on the Chang'an Avenue (Avenue of Eternal Peace) at the
foot of the Rostrum.
</P>
<P>
The show, at which outstanding singers and dancers from all
parts of the country will contribute an excellent combination of
traditional and modern performances, started with dragon and lion
dancing, a repertoire in Chinese traditional festivities.
</P>
<P>
Dancing below the Tian'anmen Rostrum are two "mighty dragons"
and nearly 100 cute "lions." The lion dancers wear two different
kinds of costumes, which represent two different styles of lion
dancing from north and south China.
</P>
<P>
The "dragons" and "lions" are followed by 14 teams of drum
dancers, who perform 14 different kinds of Chinese folk drum
dances, including those from Tibet and Xinjiang, two autonomous
regions in west China.
</P>
<P>
According to a director of the show, all performing teams in
the show will march through the Tian'anmen section of the Chang'an
Avenue from east to west, performing all the way. The entire show
is expected to last two hours. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Opening Performance of Beijing National Day Soiree </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The opening performance of the
grand National Day soiree which just opened on the Tian'anmen
Square in downtown Beijing was dragon and lion dancing, a
repertoire in Chinese traditional festivities.
</P>
<P>
Amidst the deafening sound of gongs and drums, two "mighty
dragons" and nearly 100 "lions" ran from both sides into the "
central performance zone" below the Tian'anmen Rostrum. They
started performance to the rhythm of a huge drum, which, 1.8
meters in diameter and dubbed "Drum King," is placed on a float.
</P>
<P>
The lion dancers wear two different kinds of costumes, which
represent two different styles of lion dancing in China. The "
northern lion" costumes, which are very popular in areas north of
the Yangtze River, give the "lions" a very powerful and elegant
appearance. The "southern lions" costumes, however, look pretty,
cute and flexible, and thus have always been a favorite with south
China residents, especially those in Guangdong province, Hong Kong
and Macao.
</P>
<P>
In the eyes of many Chinese, dragon and lion dancing is not
only a folk performance for holiday celebrations, but also a
solemn way to pray for good luck and happiness.
</P>
<P>
The lion and dragon dancers are followed by 14 drum dancing
teams from all over the country, each with some 100 performers.
They are from a dozen provinces and autonomous regions, including
Gansu, Henan, Jiangsu, Shaanxi, Shanxi, Xinjiang, Shandong, Yunnan
and Tibet, and all the drums they carry are different, ranging
from waist drums, hand drums to flower drums and Taiping (Peace)
drums.
</P>
<P>
The drum dancing teams passed through the Tian'anmen section of
the Chang'an Avenue from east to west in an orderly manner, while
different drum music mixed to form an amazingly exciting melody.
The soiree came to a climax shortly after its opening.
</P>
<P>
With 100,000 people singing, dancing and cheering, the Chang'an
Avenue and the Tian'anmen Square became the largest stage in the
world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
