<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Capable of Developing Advanced Missiles: Expert (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Facts have demonstrated that
China is capable of developing internationally advanced missiles,
renowned expert Liang Shoupan said today after watching on TV the
display of missiles in the National Day military parade in central
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The tactical and strategic missiles featured today are
comparable to those made by developed countries, said Liang at his
office.
</P>
<P>
"I can confidently tell you that Chinese missiles are, at the
very least, not as backward as what some Westerners say. As for
whether China's missiles are advanced or not, we know the answer,
so do the Western expert,"
</P>
<P>
In a blue jacket, Liang is easily taken as a common retired
worker. Yet, he is one of the four most respected figures in
Chinese missile and aerospace circles. The others are Ren Xinmin,
Tu Shou'e and Huang Weilu.
</P>
<P>
Liang, 83, is a graduate of the prestigious Qinghua University
and received his master's degree at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology of the United States in 1939. He returned to China in
the early 1940s.
</P>
<P>
The expert has been involved in China's missile and aerospace
technology development starting from the 1950s and led the design
team of China's first ground-to-ground missile.
</P>
<P>
"It has been proved and will continue to be proved that you can
not expect to get the most advanced military technologies from
others. You must develop it on your own. China has succeeded
thanks to its cherished spirit of self-reliance and hard-working,"
Liang said.
</P>
<P>
He recalled that China decided to develop missile technology in
April, 1956. In September of the same year, the Fifth Institute of
the Ministry of Defense was set up, with Qian Xuesen as the
director. More than 30 experts and 100 university graduates were
called in.
</P>
<P>
The then Soviet Union had promised to help China develop
missile technology. But with the souring of bilateral relations
between the two countries, the Soviet Union said they could only
sell two missile samples to China.
</P>
<P>
At that point, Marshal Nie Rongzhen, who was in charge of the
mission, held that China should develop the missile technology by
itself.
</P>
<P>
"At that conference, I told Marshal Nie that China can do it on
its own. It's true that we even didn't know what a missile looked
like. But no one in the world had seen a missile before it was
developed. If other people can do it, why we Chinese can not,"
Liang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Capable of Developing Advanced Missiles: Expert (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chairman Mao Zedong soon approved the report, adding that they
should not only be the principles in developing China's defense
technology, but also the principles in developing the whole
industry of new China.
</P>
<P>
Liang said from then to the early 1960s, China established its
own missile development bases and laboratories.
</P>
<P>
In April 1960, the group headed by Liang manufactured China's
first ground-to-ground tactical missile.
</P>
<P>
On November 5, 1960, three months after the withdrawal of the
Soviet Union experts, China successfully launched its first short-
range missile, marking a turning point in the history of China's
military armament, Liang said.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1960s, China also developed ballistic missiles,
anti-ship missiles, surface-to-air missiles and reported
breakthrough in preliminary research of various missiles and in
the fields of some single technologies, Liang said.
</P>
<P>
By 1964, China had established a research team for liquid-fuel
ballistic missiles and another for solid-fuel ballistic missiles,
paving the way for the development of new generations of strategic
missiles in the future, he added.
</P>
<P>
Liang pointed out China developed its missile and other
advanced military technologies independently, as Western nations
had been imposing an economic and military blockage on the country
from the 1950s until China's reform and opening-up in the late
1970s.
</P>
<P>
After 40 years of development, China has reported a remarkable
progress in its missile technology and has developed a whole
series of missiles, including medium-range, long-range and
ballistic missiles, as well as anti-ship, anti-air, air-to-air,
air-to-surface missiles.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese people can be proud of the advanced missiles on
show in the military parade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
