<HEADLINE> Seoul Asks Washington to Look into Alleged Civilian Massacre by US Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 1 (Xinhua) -- South Korea Friday asked the
United States to investigate the allegation by the Associated
Press that U.S. troops killed hundreds of innocent South Korean
civilians during the Korean War in 1950.
</P>
<P>
"We have started contacting the U.S. State and Defense
Departments through diplomatic channels to confirm facts related
to the issue," said South Korean Foreign Ministry spokesman Chang
Chul-kyoon.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean ministry will collect information on the
massacre, including declassified documents from the United States
and documents from the suit filed in 1997 by scores of the
massacre survivors, Chang added.
</P>
<P>
The Associated Press, quoting declassified U.S. documents and
testimonies from U.S. veterans who witnessed or participated in
the killings and from South Korean survivors, reported that U.S.
troops shot some 400 South Koreans, many of them women and
children, as a defense measure against disguised enemy soldiers in
Nogunri of North Chungchong Province, South Korea in 1950.
</P>
<P>
The probe by South Korea came one day after U.S. President Bill
Clinton said Thursday his government will investigate the incident,
the second of its kind by U.S. troops after the My Lai massacre in
1968 during the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
South Korean opposition Grand National Party President Lee Hoi-
chang called Friday for an immediate fact-finding mission on the
reported mass killing of South Korean civilians by the U.S army.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. military should make an apology for the killings and
compensate the victims if the AP report is confirmed as true, Lee
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
