<HEADLINE> 19 Taken Hostage in Myanmar Embassy in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Nineteen people were taken
hostage in Myanmar embassy in Thailand on Friday by 12 gunmen, one
of whom was later taken into custody by Thai police after stepping
outside the embassy, a well-informed source said.
</P>
<P>
The gunman was seen stepping out of the embassy at about 3 p.m.
local time (0800 GMT) and was immediately taken into custody by
the Thai policemen surrounding the embassy for interrogation.
</P>
<P>
The gunmen dashed into the Myanmar Embassy in Thailand at about
11:45 a.m. local time (0445 GMT). Soon after that shots of guns
were heard and residents living nearby reported to the police.
</P>
<P>
At first, some 22 people were taken hostage but later two Thai
policemen and the daughter of the Myanmar ambassador to Thailand
were released.
</P>
<P>
A counselor of the Myanmar embassy is among the hostages. But
it is still unclear whether the ambassador is also detained.
</P>
<P>
Chatchawal Suksumjit, spokesman of Royal Thai Police, told
Xinhua that the number of the gunmen was 12, but he declined to
confirm the exact number of hostages.
</P>
<P>
The gunmen, believed to be Myanmar students living in Thailand,
were reportedly carrying eight Germany-made SK machine guns and 20
grenades.
</P>
<P>
Thai police has blocked the roads leading to the Myanmar
embassy in downtown Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
Sanan Kachornprasart, Thailand's Interior Minister, said after
inspecting the scene that it is still unknown whether there is any
casualty in the embassy.
</P>
<P>
The Thai police is conducting a negotiation with the gunmen.
However, the demand of the gunmen and the result of the
negotiation are yet to be made clear. 
</P>
</TEXT>
