<HEADLINE> India's Exports Grow by 10.16 percent in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 1 (Xinhua) -- India's exports scored a
double-digit growth of 10.16 percent in August after dipping to
2.11 percent in July, according to official trade data released
Friday.
</P>
<P>
However, imports grew at a faster rate of 19.3 percent in the
month, widening the trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
In dollar terms, exports in April-August stood at 14.11 billion
U.S. dollars compared to 13.49 billion U.S. dollars, recording a
4.62 percent growth over last year.
</P>
<P>
Imports during the first five months (April-August) of the
current fiscal year rose by 3.94 percent to 18.07 billion U.S.
dollars against 17.39 billion U.S. dollars in the same period last
year on account of a sharp 56.45 percent growth in oil imports.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, trade deficit widened to 3.96 billion U.S. dollars
in April-August from 3.9 billion U.S. dollars in the same period
last year, showing a rise of 1.59 percent.
</P>
<P>
The country's exports touched double digits in May and June at
11.68 percent and 11.14 percent, respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
