<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Special Economic Zones Going Strong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- One float with a model of a
high-speed train loaded with the products of China's special
economic zones is part of today's National Day procession.
</P>
<P>
China began its opening up policy in 1979 by establishing the
four special economic zones (SEZ) in Shenzhen, Zhuhai, Shantou,
and Xiamen along the southeastern and southern coast. In 1988,
Hainan, China's second largest island, was made the country's
fifth and largest SEZ.
</P>
<P>
Numerous economic and technological development zones have also
been established in the suburbs of coastal cities. There are now
32 state-level economic and technological development zones, all
of which have become industrial production and high-tech
development centers with overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
Following the late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping's study tour
of south China in 1992, the Chinese Government declared the
opening up of the Yangtze River Valley, the economically vibrant
heartland of China. At the head of the move was the opening of
Shanghai's Pudong New Area. By March of this year, Pudong had 5,
581 direct overseas-funded projects worth 28 billion U.S. dollars
in all.
</P>
<P>
In the 1990s, the SEZs began restructuring their industries and
by now have largely relocated the old labor-intensive operations
and put technology- and capital-intensive enterprises in their
place.
</P>
<P>
The Shenzhen SEZ had 9.027 billion U.S. dollars worth of
turnover in the first five months of this year, up 12.6 percent, 4.
549 billion U.S. dollars worth of exports, down 1.8 percent, and
imports worth 4.479 billion U.S. dollars, up 32.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Zhuhai SEZ in Guangdong Province had economic growth of 9.4
percent in the first five months of this year and the Xiamen SEZ
in Fujian Province had a GDP of 19.12 billion yuan from January to
June, up 15.9 percent on a year-on-year basis, and double the
national average of 7.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Shantou SEZ, which is also in Guangdong Province, has
introduced a policy to promote high-tech development and sharpen
its competitive edge that calls for the city to provide 10 million
yuan (1.2 million U.S. dollars) in special funding annually over
the next three years to support high-tech development. Shantou
currently has 41 high-tech enterprises with a combined annual
output of 3.2 billion yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
