<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 08:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Rejects Dialog out of U.N. Resolutions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides said Friday night Cyprus will not participate in any
dialog on a Cyprus settlement which is not within the parameters
of relevant U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
In a message on the occasion of Cyprus' 39th anniversary of
independence on October 1, Clerides said "we are fed up with
seeing the Turkish side defying and violating U.N. resolutions
... as well as the constant efforts of some countries to
intervene so as to help Turkey not to suffer the consequences of
its negative stance."
</P>
<P>
Clerides returned to Cyprus in the early hours on Friday after
seeing a disappointing round of contacts over the Cyprus issue in
New York which culminated in a meeting between U.S. President Bill
Clinton and Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit.
</P>
<P>
The meeting that had been expected to boost hopes for the
renewal of talks, ended up with another round of contacts by
Clinton's Cyprus envoy, Alfred Moses, who is due in the region
next week.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
The international community has been trying for decades to
reunite the island through a bicommunal federation formula.
</P>
<P>
But the Turkish Cypriots and their staunch supporter Turkey
have conditioned the resumption of peace talks, that have been
stalled since 1997, on the international recognition of the
breakaway Turkish republic in northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Clerides said if Moses' forthcoming visit to the region fails,
the international community should take other decisions and
measures.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed the Greek Cypriot side's readiness "to enter
into talks without preconditions and to negotiate with flexibility
and courage," within the framework of the relevant U.N. Security
Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Clerides pointed out that the fate of any talks on Cyprus
depends mainly on the Turkish side as well as the stand of the
international community vis-a-vis Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Referring to recent developments on Cyprus, Clerides said
that "unfortunately, this time too Turkey's stand is negative."
</P>
<P>
At Tuesday's Clinton-Ecevit meeting, Ecevit repeated the view
that the Cyprus peace talks would take place only until the
breakaway state is internationally recognized.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leukemia-Hit Nyerere in Critical Condition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian founding
president Julius Nyerere, admitted in a London hospital for
leukemia last week, has been in critical condition since Thursday
night, an official press release said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"His condition became worse last night and the doctors are
trying to rescue him," said the release signed by Geoffrey Nkurlu,
Press Secretary to Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Mkapa urged his people again to pray for Nyerere's
recovery, the release said.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere, 77, was admitted to St. Thomas Hospital on September
23 when he was not able to speak with a bit consciousness.
</P>
<P>
Medical tests showed that he has been steadily improved since
then but on September 29 he developed jaundice, a condition which
has been described as normal by doctors treating him.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa confirmed at an emergency news conference in the State
House last Sunday that Nyerere is suffering from chronic
lymphocytic leukemia, or blood cancer.
</P>
<P>
Since Mkapa's confirmation, many Tanzanians have answered his
call to pray for the recovery of their Father of the Nation.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian Minister for Regional Administration and Local
Governments Kingunge Ngombale-Mwiru Tuesday was dispatched to
London to join Nyerere's wife and two daughters to monitor his
condition.
</P>
<P>
Born in the town of Butiama, Tanganyika in 1922, Nyerere led
the Tanganyika African National Union (TANU) to win independence
from British colonial rule in 1961.
</P>
<P>
He also united Tanganyika and Zanzibar as one republic in 1964
and became its first president until he retired in 1985.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere, who preferred to be called Mwalimu in Kiswahili or
teacher in English, has been a prominent leader on many
pan-African issues.
</P>
<P>
He has successfully assembled the warring factions of Burundi
to start a tortuous peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Newspapers Praise China's Achievements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnamese Communist Party's
daily and the Vietnamese Army's daily Friday praised China's great
achievements in their editorials marking the 50th anniversary of
the founding of the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
The party's daily Nhan Dan (People) said that the achievements
China gained over the past half century have testified to the
appropriate path chosen by the Chinese people for building
socialism with Chinese characteristics.
</P>
<P>
The handover of Hong Kong and the scheduled return of Macau to
China later this year prove an irreversible trend and desire on
the part of the Chinese people to fulfill the national
reunification, said Nhan Dan's editorial titled "Celebrate the
Great National Day of Fraternal Chinese People."
</P>
<P>
The paper affirmed that the Communist Party, the State and the
people of Vietnam support that legitimate desire and hold that
there is only one China, with Taiwan being it's inseparable part.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper highlights the time-honored Sino-Vietnamese
friendship as neighbors with common mountains and rivers.
</P>
<P>
In celebration of the glorious historical day of the fraternal
people of all nationalities in China, the Vietnamese people, once
again, express their sincere and profound gratitude towards the
Chinese people for their strong support and valuable assistance to
Vietnam in the past struggle for national liberation as well as in
the on-going process of renovation, industrialization and
modernization for the goal of a rich people, a strong country and
a just and civilized society, said the Nhan Dan.
</P>
<P>
The friendship and cooperation between the parties and states
of Vietnam and China have seen encouraging steps of development in
many fields in recent years, said the editorial, adding that the
two peoples are doing their utmost to develop the fraternal
friendship and multi-form cooperation in the next century.
</P>
<P>
On this occasion, Quan Doi Nhan Dan (People's Army) daily on
Friday also carried an editorial titled "The Glorious
Semicentennial of the People's Republic of China," describing the
great success of China's revolution, the birth of the People's
Republic of China and the great achievements of the Communist
Party, the Government and the people of China over the past half
century as one of the most outstanding events in the 20th century.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
