<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Anniversary Parade Ushers in New Century (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Tens of thousands of colorful
balloons and homing pigeons flew up to the sky. More than 100,000
children surged toward Tian'anmen or the Gate of Heavenly Peace,
capering and cheering to the Chinese leaders on the Tian'anmen
Rostrum, who waved to them in acknowledgement energetically from
time to time.
</P>
<P>
This scene brought the celebrations for the 50th founding
anniversary of new China to a climax when it came to an end at
around 12:00 at noon.
</P>
<P>
About 500,000 armymen and civilians took part in the grand
celebrations today. The youngest participator is Zhang Wenzhe, a
two-year-old kid. The girl got restless in the parade and kept
looking around from her father's shoulders.
</P>
<P>
Liu Baoqin, 70, strode past the Tian'anmen Square, drawing
himself up as he did 50 years ago in the parade marking the birth
of new China.
</P>
<P>
"My stamina and patriotism are enough to put me through all the
parade process." Liu said.
</P>
<P>
The anniversary paraders represented people of various
backgrounds, ranging from civil servants, religious people,
workers to scientists. Most are eager to tell the reporters how
honored they feel to join the last anniversary parade of this
century.
</P>
<P>
Some paraders said they feel a bit nervous because of the
unusual significance of the celebrations. "A total of 1,000 people
have to hold aloft a huge National Flag. We have to do this very
cautiously because it will be such a shame if a ripple appears on
the flag," Liu Yawei, an armed police officer, told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The civilian parade was held right after the military parade.
Although it lasted only about 50 minutes, it represented the five-
decade course of the People's Republic and its promising future.
Featuring a long queue of floats, a myriad of banners, and
formation after formation of dancing and singing paraders, the
procession ended with a float modeled after a manned spacecraft
ready for take-off, which represents the real destination of the
paraders in the future.
</P>
<P>
Portraits of Mao Zedong, Deng Xiaoping, and Jiang Zemin
appeared in the parade, who are the respective cores of the three
generations of China's central collective leadership. The Chinese
Communist Party was founded in 1921.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
