<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Not to Be Harmed by Japan Nuclear Fallout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines will be spared
from any radiation as a result of nuclear disaster in Japan,
because of the weak northeasterly monsoon prevailing at this time
of the year, an expert said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Guillermo Dulay, chief of the Philippine Atmospheric,
Geophysical and Astronomical Services Administration (PAGASA) was
quoted by the Philippine News Agency as saying that the
probability that the nuclear fallout from Japan will reach the
Philippines is nil.
</P>
<P>
It was reported there were a number of recorded deaths in the
incident in Tokai, Japan, Thursday and about 300,000 people near
the disaster area were advised to stay indoors.
</P>
<P>
"The probability that the fallout will reach the Philippines is
low, because of the weak northeasterly winds at this time," Dulay
said.
</P>
<P>
Dulay said the coming of a typhoon would further reduce the
risk that radioactive elements will hit the Philippines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
