<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Calls for More ASEAN Commitment to East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of Defense
William Cohen Friday called for more commitment from the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) countries in the
East Timor issue.
</P>
<P>
If "the instability and terror" that took place in East Timor
go unaddressed, it will have the potential for having a very large
consequences that go beyond East Timor itself," Cohen said at a
press conference held here Friday.
</P>
<P>
"So I think ASEAN countries should take a reasonable response
to trying to bring peace and stability (to East Timor) in the
situation," Cohen said at the press conference after meeting Thai
Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai and Thai Supreme Commander Mongkon
Ampornpisit earlier Friday.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN countries, all of which Cohen believed have interests in
the peace and stability in East Timor, will have to decide for
themselves what contribution they will make to the peacekeeping
mission in terms of troops and financial contributions, the U.S.
Defense Secretary said.
</P>
<P>
Cohen also said that he has pointed out to the Indonesian
government that the international community is watching closely
what role Indonesia will play in the East Timor issue.
</P>
<P>
"It's beneficial to Indonesia to play a constructive and
positive role in bringing peace and stability to East Timor," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He also called for disarmament of pro-Indonesian militia both
in East and West Timor.
</P>
<P>
As for Thailand, Cohen said the country is playing a leading
role by sending some 1,500 military personnel to the United
Nations peacekeeping force in East Timor (INTERFET).
</P>
<P>
Thailand's Major General Songkitti Chakkabart has been
appointed Deputy Commander of INTERFET.
</P>
<P>
Cohen also promised to provide financial assistance for the
cash-strapped Thai military on its transportation of troops and
equipment to East Timor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
