<HEADLINE> Foreign Firms in Zambia Accused of Flouting Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- A Zambian official has accused
multinational companies of flouting his country's trade mark laws
by transferring their trade marks without providing necessary
technology to local agents.
</P>
<P>
Assistant Registrar of the Patents and Companies, Wilbroad
Mulenga, urged the government to enact measures to protect local
companies against business malpractices of the multinational
companies in the use of trade marks, according Times of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The official was quoted as saying that a recent study shows
that the multinational companies are terminating trade mark
contracts at will when the local companies pay huge royalties.
</P>
<P>
"We feel Zambian companies need more protection against abusive
 tendencies by multinationals and government has the means to
apply pressure to force them to abide through the enactment of
stiffer laws," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said few companies know the use of the patent office and
attributed this to lack of information.
</P>
<P>
The ministry of commerce, trade and industry has recently
constituted a committee that will spearhead the speedy compliance
of provision, Mulenga said. 
</P>
