<HEADLINE> Air Quality in Chinese Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The air quality in most of
Chinese cities dropped this week, according to a report released
today by the China Environment Monitoring Center.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Lanzhou, capital of northwest China's
Gansu Province, was hit by a sandy weather and the air was
seriously polluted.
</P>
<P>
From September 24-30, Yantai, Beihai, Ningbo, Xiamen, Haikou
and 26 other cities including Shanghai, Hangzhou, Guilin, Shenzhen
and Suzhou reported good air quality.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Zhengzhou, Beijing, Chongqing, Xi'an,, Urumqi,
Taiyuan, Guangzhou, and Tianjin reported moderate air pollution
during the week.
</P>
<P>
The major pollutant in Beijing, Guangzhou and Shanghai was
nitrogen oxide, while in Chongqing, sulfur dioxide was the main
pollutant, and most of other Chinese cities suffered from
suspended particles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
