<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Three Gorges Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The Three Gorges Hydro-Electric
Power Project, Xiaolangdi Dam Project, and other water control
projects are represented by a float displaying China's
achievements in water conservation in the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges Hydro-electric Power project on the Yangtze
River is the biggest of its kind in the world. Its purpose is to
increase flood control, power generating capacity, and shipping on
the river. It has three parts: construction of a dam, resettlement
of people, and power facilities.
</P>
<P>
It is located near Yichang in central China's Hubei Province
and cost an estimated 50.09 billion yuan (at May, 1993 prices).
It will have 26 generating units with a combined capacity of 18.2
million kw and an annual output of 84.7 billion kwh. The river was
dammed at the project site on November 8, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The resettlement of people living in the dam area started in
October of 1992. The entire project is scheduled for completion in
the year 2009.
</P>
<P>
Construction work and the use of funds has been going on well
according to plan, with 42 billion yuan having been spent by the
end of August of 1999 and 8.4 million cubic meters of concrete
having been poured, according to one project official.
</P>
<P>
More than 4,200 contracts have been signed for the project,
worth 32 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The project entered its second phase of construction with the
damming of the Yangtze in November of 1997. The cofferdams built
for the second phase were able to withstand last year's and this
year's summer floods on the river.
</P>
<P>
The second phase is scheduled for completion by 2003. By then,
18 million cubic meters of concrete will have been poured.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Steel Output Of 100 Million Tons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- In the National Day processions,
one float has a huge number one.
</P>
<P>
It means that China's fifty-year growth has made it the world's
largest steel producer. Its output last year was 114 million tons.
</P>
<P>
China has complete steel production system and 10 key steel
enterprises that account for 50 percent of the country's steel.
</P>
<P>
From 1949 to 1998, fixed assets spending in the steel industry
totaled 478.7 billion yuan. During that period, the sector had 553
billion yuan in pre-tax profits. But, in the early 1950s, China
could only produce 100 types of low-grade rolled steel and had an
annual steel output of 158,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
To improve the quality of steel and efficiency in the sector
this year, China decided to cut steel production by 10 percent and
it will push for the renovation of older enterprises, develop hi-
tech value-added products, and improve the proportion of high-
quality steel to make China a real iron and steel power.
</P>
</TEXT>
