<HEADLINE> Chinese People's Health Improved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The National Day parade included
a group of medical personnel accompanying a float with a bird,
lotus flowers, and a red cross.
</P>
<P>
It is there for the 14.42 million Chinese health workers to
reflect the coordinated social, economic, and ecological
development in China.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, China had 310,000 health care
institutions with a total of 3.14 million beds.
</P>
<P>
China had 5,907 epidemic and disease prevention stations
employing 220,000 people and 2,724 maternal and infant health-care
institutions employing 73,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The infant mortality rate has dropped from 74 per thousand 20
years ago to 40.9 per thousand and the death rate among children
below the age of 5 has dropped by about a third.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, there were 141.7 deaths from diarrhea per 100,000
children, a 67.8 percent decrease from 1991.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five decades, China has reduced the mortality
rate from 30 per thousand to 6.5 per thousand and the mortality
rate of new-born infants from 200 per thousand to 33.1 per
thousand, and the life expectancy of Chinese has gone from 35 to
71 years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
