<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Cut 60,000 Jobs in Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 1 (Xinhua) -- About 60,000 civil servants will
be sacked between next year and the year 2001, a senior Kenyan
official has announced.
</P>
<P>
The East African Standard daily Friday quoted Permanent
Secretary of the Presidential Office Zachayo Cheruiyot as saying
that the move would help cut expenditure and improve efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Ministries, provinces and districts have been directed to
establish civil service reform committees, performance
improvement teams and payroll audit units, Cheruiyot said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said such organizations would identify the posts that need
to be abolished, privatized, commercialized, contracted or
transferred elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
Cheruiyot revealed that Kenya had sacked 44,000 public servants
between 1992 and 1998 but failed to reduce government
expenditure.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government aimed to reduce staff by 30 percent
and consequently cut expenditure 20 percent by 2001.
</P>
<P>
The retrenchment is part of the economic recovery plan
initiated by Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi. Kenya has
witnessed a recession in the last several years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
