<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN, CER to Explore Common Free Trade Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast
Asian Nations and the countries of the Australia-New Zealand
Closer Economic Relations Trade Agreement (CER) have agreed to
into the feasibility of establishing an AFTA (ASEAN Free Trade
AREA)-CER free trade area by 2010.
</P>
<P>
The agreement on establishing a high-level joint task force for
this purpose was reached at the Fourth Informal Consultation
meeting between ASEAN economic ministers and ministers from the
CER countries.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held at the end of the consultation
meeting, Singapore Minister for Trade and Industry George Yeo said
the ministers unanimously nominated Cesar Virata, former prime
minister of the Philippines as the leader of the task force.
</P>
<P>
A press statement released after the consultation meeting said
this proposed free trade area should be WTO-consistent and the
study would examine the potential of an AFTA-CER free trade area
and the adjustments required, including the flexibility needed by
the four new members of ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, the study will be completed within
12 months and will be submitted to the 32nd ASEAN Economic
Ministers (AEM) meeting for consideration in October 2000 in
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The statement also said statistics show that ASEAN's exports to
the CER increased by 16.6 percent to 9.7 billion U.S. dollars in
1998 from 8.3 billion U.S. dollars while imports from the CER fell
24.4 percent from 9.3 billion U.S. dollars to 6.7 billion U.S.
dollars in the year.
</P>
<P>
The statement also said that the proportion of ASEAN trade
with CER increased to 2.8 percent of the total in 1998 from 2.5
percent in 1997. ASEAN's previous trade deficit with the CER of
960.7 million U.S. dollars turned into a surplus of 2.98 billion
U.S. dollars in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
