<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Improved Environmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- A large number of young people
dressed in flowery garments accompanying a float with the image of
a globe are part of the National Day procession.
</P>
<P>
They reflects the love of the Chinese people for the globe and
their attempts to protect the environment and contribute to
mankind.  The Chinese government has paid a great deal of
attention to environmental issues arising from population growth
and economic development, and has made protecting the environment
an important part of the improvement of the standard of living and
quality of life.
</P>
<P>
China has more than 30 administrative decrees on environmental
protection and had 500 water pollution control projects for a
number of major coastal cities and lakes during the Ninth Five-
Year Plan (1996-2000), which called for 56 billion yuan in
spending.
</P>
<P>
China spent more than 80 billion yuan (about 9.6 billion U.S.
dollars) last year on the environment, more than one percent of
the country's GDP.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1950s, the Chinese government has had large-scale
tree planting and in the past 20 years there has been an annual
increase of four million hectares of afforested land, with 2.4
billion trees planted by volunteers each year. China has preserved
34.3 million ha. of afforested land.
</P>
<P>
China plans to cut the amount of sulfur dioxide emissions by 14
percent before the end of 2000 and 42 percent by 2010. A plan has
been drawn up to control acid rain and sulfur dioxide in 11.4
percent of the country, in 175 prefectures and cities, mostly in
the southern and central parts of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress In China's Aerospace Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Among the many floats in today's
National Day parade, there is a blue and silver float with
satellites, rockets, and missiles that reflects China's
achievements in its aerospace industry over the past 40 years.
</P>
<P>
Since the late 1950's, China has developed several types of
Long March carrier rocket for commercial use and various types of
satellites for experiments, outerspace sensing, meteorology, and
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
China has built three launch sites and a global satellite
telemetering and tracking network. This satellite technology has
brought tremendous social and economic benefits to industry,
agriculture, communications, finance, and other areas.
</P>
<P>
China has now entered a new stage in commercial satellites
using its technological strength and is doing research on putting
manned missions in outer space with its own spacecraft by the year
2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
