<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Govt Urged to Cut Expenditure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The Confederation of Zimbabwe
Industries has urged the government to make drastic cuts on its
non-essential expenditure as the financial situation of the
country continues to worsen.
</P>
<P>
A solution must be found for the crippling debt which has
reached some 3. 47 billion U.S. dollars, president of the
confederation Kumbirai Katsande said in Harare Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's foreign debt stands at 2.37 billion dollars) while
the domestic at 1.1 billion dollars, according to the industrial
leader.
</P>
<P>
"The increase of debt is a result of an inequitable balance
between expenditure and revenue," the Herald newspaper Friday
quoted Katsande as saying.
</P>
<P>
"A major rethink, a culture of change on such things as the
size of government itself is called for," he said.
</P>
<P>
While welcoming recent statements by President Robert Mugabe
reaffirming his government's commitment to economic reform,
Katsande said such commitment needed to be speedily translated
into resolute actions by all arms of the government.
</P>
<P>
"We are now in a most desperate situation and the government
must at last make and implement the unavoidable decisions," he
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"We call on the government to be decisive in dealing with
inflation which clearly cannot be allowed to continue to increase.
 The longer government delays to act, the more difficult, if not
hopeless, our situation becomes," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's year-on-year inflation rate in August this year
reached 68.8 percent. 
</P>
