<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Non-Public Sector Helping China's Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The National Day processions has
a float with a rainbow, flying seagulls, colored ribbon, and
breaking waves.
</P>
<P>
The rainbow stands for China's rapid economic development of
various forms of ownership. The seagulls reflect non-public
enterprises, while the colored ribbon symbolizes the free
operation of that sector, which has become an important part of
China's socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
The government is encouraging the participation of such
essential factors of production as capital and technology.
</P>
<P>
The non-public sector includes not only private businesses, but
also collectively-owned enterprises and joint stock companies
without State capital. By the end of last year, China had 699
million people employed in the sector, a 3.57 million increase
from 1997. The urban private sector accounted for 32.32 million
people, an increase of 5.63 million from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
These figures indicate that the non-public sector is assuming
an increasingly important role in providing employment in China at
a time when the State-owned sector, which is undergoing profound
reforms, can no longer provide so many job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Almost half of China's annual tax revenues now comes from the
non-public sector, the main growth area for tax revenues. The
private sector maintained its momentum this year. The State
Administration for Industry and Commerce reports that China had 67,
100 new private companies during the January-March period this
year, with an average registered capital of 616,500 yuan for each.
</P>
<P>
China re-defined the status and role of the private sector in
March of this year by adding the non-public sector as "an
important component of the country's socialist market economy" to
its Constitution. This has given a strong boost to the private
sector.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
