<HEADLINE> Signing of EAC Treaty Postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The signing of the East
African Community (EAC) Treaty has been postponed again to the
end of November due to trade disagreement.
</P>
<P>
The treaty was due to be signed this month by the heads of
state of the three member nations -- Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania,
the East African Standard newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
However, the ministers of the three countries responsible for
the regional body have agreed to go ahead with process despite
continuous disagreement on a customs union to facilitate free
trade, according to a recent meeting held in Arusha, a northern
town of Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
This is the third postpone for the signing of the treaty aimed
at rekindling the collapsed East African community in 1977. The
treaty was first scheduled to be signed in December 1998 and was
then postponed to July this year which was not realized due to
rifts over trade and labor.
</P>
<P>
EAC Executive Secretary Francis Muthaura confirmed that this
time around,
</P>
<P>
the treaty would be finally signed despite the rifts touching on
custom union visa a vis common market, saying there would be no
more negotiations on the subject.
</P>
<P>
"The custom union is the entry point of the EAC then it is
followed with the establishment of a common market," the
secretariat boss said, adding that the common market is at a more
advanced stage of the regional integration
</P>
<P>
Uganda's first Deputy Prime Minister, Eriya Kategaya, who
attended the two-day meeting, said the main issue of discussion
was the adoption of the proposed treaty with the aim to create a
big market for the region.
</P>
<P>
Attended the meeting also included Kenya's Trade and Tourism
Minister Nicholas Biwott and Tanzania's Minister for Commerce and
Industry Idd Simba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
