<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 126 Million Older Persons in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- China has 126 million people
above the age of 60, one fifth of the world total such population,
said information from the National Bureau of Statistics (NBS).
</P>
<P>
Today is the international festival of older persons.
</P>
<P>
The NBS sources also disclosed that by the end of this year,
China's number of people above 60 will account for ten percent of
the country's total population.
</P>
<P>
By the year of 2000, seven percent of the country's population
will be persons above 65, which will demonstrate that China has
entered an old-age society.
</P>
<P>
China has made progress in economy, science and technology,
medical care and improvement in people's living standards.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of the country's social and economic progress, and
the success in family planning, China has had an decrease in birth
rate and mortality, and the country's natural population growth
rate is also brought down to below 10 per thousand, which has in
turn raised the aging population.
</P>
<P>
China's aging population will exceed 130 million next year; by
the mid-21st century, China will have about 400 million elderly,
the biggest population of old people in the world.
</P>
<P>
United Nations statistics show that by 2001, the worldwide
population of people over 60 will hit 630 million, and is expected
to reach one billion in 2020.
</P>
<P>
The year 1999 was designated by the U.N. as the International
Year of Older Persons in a bid to bring international and national
attention to the needs of older persons in all societies  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
