<HEADLINE> Kenya Tea Production Expected Down 20% in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Kenya expects its tea production
this year to fall by 20 percent to 235 million kilograms from 294
million kilograms in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Stephen Nkanata, Chief Executive of the Tea Board of Kenya said
Thursday that the output fell to 152 million kilograms in the year
to August, down by 22 percent from 195 million kilograms in the
same period last year's.
</P>
<P>
The chief executive said severe drought in the main tea-growing
area had undermined the production in the first eight month of the
year.
</P>
<P>
"We have had good rains in the west of the Rift and the crop is
already coming in, but the east of the Rift has been severely
affected by drought," the East African Standard newspaper Friday
quoted Nkanata as saying.
</P>
<P>
Tea is one of the major foreign exchange earners for Kenya.
Last year, the east African country earned 580 million U.S.
dollars from tea exports to Britain, Pakistan, Egypt among others.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
