<HEADLINE> Lebanon Denies Reducing Service to Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon has denied a United
Nations body's accusations that the government had unjustifiably
reduced its health care services to needy Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
"The Health Ministry is obliged to secure free health care for
needy Lebanese citizens. It helps needy Palestinians when it can,"
Health Minister Karam Karam said in an interview with the Voice of
Lebanon radio Friday.
</P>
<P>
His comments came in response to charges published in a report
by the U.N. Relief and Works Agency (UNRWA) responsible for
handling Palestinian refugee affairs.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese minister explained that his "government is
suffering from a difficult economic crisis. The ministry can
barely cover the needs of Lebanese."
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, scores of Palestinian refugees staged a sit-in in
the Ain al-Hilweh Palestinian refugee camp in the country's
southern port city of Sidon, the biggest among a total of 12 camps
across Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
They wanted to send a message to representatives of donor
countries who are expected to gather in Amman, Jordan, to discuss
further financial contributions to UNRWA, according to sources at
the refugee camp.
</P>
<P>
After the Palestinian self-rule authority was created in 1993,
donor countries, mainly Western countries, cut their funding for
the agency, arguing the Palestinian refugee problem would soon be
solved.
</P>
<P>
The cuts, coupled with accused rampant corruption in UNRWA
ranks, have reduced the agency's ability to provide services to
some 2 million refugees still living in Lebanon, Syria, Jordan,
the West Bank and Gaza. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
