<HEADLINE> China's Information Industry Showing Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- One National Day float decorated
with a satellite, integrated circuits, large-screen terminals, and
a computer keyboard reflects China's information industry
development of the past 50 years and its role in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The Information Industry has had especially rapid development
in recent years and has become an important part of the nation's
economy. Since 1994, China has given special support to research
and development in information technology for multi-media and
Internet uses and the market has attracted a number of foreign
companies, which fund or operate more than 6,500 enterprises in
China.
</P>
<P>
China has one of the world's leading information technology
industries, with sales reaching 310 billion yuan (37 billion U.S.
dollars) in 1998, up 14.1 percent from 1997.
</P>
<P>
Sales of personal computers will reach 5.1 million in China
this year, up 25 percent from 1998. China's largest PC
manufacturer, the Legend Group, was one of the world's top 15
companies in this area in terms of market share in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has developed a framework for the
fledgling electronic commerce industry this year to help the
digital economy grow.
</P>
<P>
It has an extensive, high capacity, high speed optical fiber
network supported by satellites and microwave stations. The
optical fiber network is an estimated one million kilometers long
and reaches all provincial capitals and over 90 percent of China's
cities and counties. All provinces have satellite
telecommunications ground stations and more than 20,000 satellite
telecommunications lines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka, U.S. Sign New Extradition Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka and the United States
Thursday signed a new extradition treaty, the first ever fully
comprehensive one signed by the tropical island country, the
Government's Information Department said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The department said in a statement that the treaty, replacing a
1931 treaty signed by Britain as the colonial power, was signed by
Sri Lankan Minister of Foreign Affairs Lakshman Kadirgamar and
U.S. Acting Secretary of State Strobe Talbott in Washington.
</P>
<P>
It quoted Kadirgamar as saying the new treaty, which was
concluded early this year after a single round of talks, reflected
"current developments and advances in international state
practice, paying particularly attention to the problem of
terrorism."
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said the treaty would mean that if a member of
the separatist Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) tried to
hide in the United States after committing a crime, he or she
could be sent back to Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The need for a new extradition treaty between the two countries
was first raised by Kadirgamar during his official visit to
Washington in October 1997 as some provisions under the old one
were outdated and clumsy.
</P>
<P>
Talbott said, "The joint interest... in combating the scourge
of international crime and particularly the ever present threat of
terrorism is another reason for this to be a very timely
occasion."
</P>
<P>
The LTTE, fighting for an independent Tamil homeland in Sri
Lanka's north and east since 1983, has been designated by the U.S.
State Department as a terrorist organization and was banned at
home as well as in the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Launches New Primary Education Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's President Olusegun
Obasanjo has launched an "ambitious and costly" new education
scheme for teenagers as part of a government initiative to revive
the country's crumbling education system.
</P>
<P>
Dubbed the universal basic education (UBE) program, the new
scheme is designed to provide "compulsory, free and universal
education for teens between the ages of six and 15," the president
said in Sokoto, northeast Nigeria, Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The new scheme would help "restore interest and dignity in
learning and scholarship" after years of decline in primary school
enrolment," information reaching here Friday quoted Obasanjo as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The president said the scheme would also incorporate a program
for " producing trained teachers, a comprehensive adult literacy
program and be adequately funded."
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Education Minister Tunde Adeniran said that the new
scheme would replace the previous universal primary education
program (UPE), launched by Obasanjo as military leader in 1976.
With the scheme in operation, education would be compulsory for
the first nine years of education.
</P>
<P>
The old scheme was abandoned as "unsustainable" by subsequent
governments because of an explosion in the number of school age
children, the lack of funding, dearth of teachers and the decay in
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The new scheme was "ambitious and expensive," Obasanjo said,
adding that the cost would be borne by "everybody" as a
"legitimate investment in the children to enable them to cope with
the challenges of the future."
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's education system ran into crisis in the past 15 years
of military rule, which ended in May this year, when a combination
of poor funding and staffing and decay of infrastructure affected
the quality of graduates, creating a confidence crisis in the
education system.
</P>
<P>
When coming into power on May 29 this year, Obasanjo pledged to
address the malaise in this sector so as to provide a "solid
foundation for the country's development." 
</P>
