<HEADLINE> New Zealand Cabinet Agrees to Take 300 Timor Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Ministers of the New Zealand
Cabinet Friday formally agreed to provide refuge in the country
for up to 300 displaced persons from East Timor, Prime Minister
Jenny Shipley announced.
</P>
<P>
In a media release, Shipley said the displaced persons will be
accommodated in two locations on North Island.
</P>
<P>
"They will be here on limited purpose permits, issued initially
for three months. They will be here as guests of New Zealand and
we will ensure that their accommodation, food and health needs are
taken care of while they are here," she said.
</P>
<P>
Shipley estimated that the cost for their travel,
accommodation, food and other services for the three months would
total about five million NZ dollars (2.6 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
