<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Trade Surplus Increases in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia recorded a 7.4
percent increase in its trade surplus in August this year over
that in the same month last year, the Statistics Department
announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
The trade surplus in the month under review amounted to 6.66
billion ringgit (1.752 billion U.S. dollars) against 6.2 billion
ringgit (1.631 billion U.S. dollars) in the same month of last
year, according to the preliminary external trade statistics for
August released here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The August surplus was the 22nd consecutive monthly surplus
since November 1997 and was the second highest since December 1998
when a surplus of 6.7 billion ringgit (1.763 billion U.S. dollars)
was recorded.
</P>
<P>
A higher growth in exports of 2.8 billion ringgit (736.842
million U.S. dollars) to 27.1 billion ringgit (7.131 billion U.S.
dollars) against a growth of 2.3 billion ringgit (605.263 million
U.S. dollars) in imports to 20.4 billion ringgit (5.368 billion
U.S. dollars) led to the surplus for the month under review.
</P>
<P>
The higher exports were mainly driven by the 20.6 percent
increase in electrical and electronic products while import
growth was due to a growth of 16.2 percent in the purchase of
intermediate goods, it said.
</P>
<P>
For the first eight months of this year, Malaysia's trade
surplus rose 42.2 percent to 46.2 billion ringgit (11.105 billion
U.S. dollars) from 32.5 billion ringgit (8.552 billion U.S.
dollars) in the corresponding period of last year, the statistics
department said.
</P>
<P>
The higher surplus in the first eight months of this year was
largely due to the higher growth in exports, the department said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
