<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese-Myanmar Celebrate China's National Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Associations of Overseas Chinese
and Chinese-Myanmar residing in Myanmar's capital of Yangon
jointly held a grand meeting here Friday to celebrate the 50th
anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
Lu Zhenbin, deputy director-general of the Overseas Chinese
Chamber of Commerce, said in his speech that China underwent an
earth-shaking change in 50 years since its founding, especially in
20 years since its reform and opening of its doors to the outside
world.
</P>
<P>
Lu, who is also chairman of the Fujian Native Association,
stressed that during the period, China's economy grew at a fast
pace with the society developing all-sidedly, people's living
standard continuously improving and the comprehensive national
strength continuing to grow.
</P>
<P>
The broad masses of the overseas Chinese in Myanmar take this
as their pride, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of China's reunification, Lu said, "Taiwan is an
inalienable part of China and this will always remain a
unchangeable fact. Chinese all over the world strongly anticipate
an early reunification of their motherland."
</P>
<P>
He warned that Lee Teng-hui's "two-country concept" is doomed
to fail, adding that Lee himself will lose his standing and
reputation and will become a culprit of history.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Chinese Ambassador Liang Dong said in half a
century, China has turned from a backward old China to a basically
prosperous new China full of vigor and hope.
</P>
<P>
He added that "we have every reason to believe that in the
forthcoming new century, Chinese nationalities are sure to
overcome the difficulties and obstacles in the course of advance,
and would contribute its part to world peace and development with
its more brilliant achievements."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the meeting were also Wang Yueying, vice-chairman
of the Overseas Chinese Women's Association, and Chen Wanchang,
chairman of the Overseas Chinese Arts and Culture Association.
</P>
<P>
Present on the occasion were nearly 300 representatives of
different associations of overseas Chinese and Chinese-Myanmar in
Yangon.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, different associations of overseas Chinese and
Chinese-Myanmar will stage grand arts and cultural performances
here on Sunday in celebration of the Chinese National Day with
varied programs in praise of New China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
