<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiscal Deficit Rises 26 Percent in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The fiscal deficit rose by 26
percent to 481.26 billion rupees (11.19 billion U.S. dollars) in
the first five months (April-August) of 1999-2000 fiscal year as
against 381.49 billion rupees (8.87 billion U.S. dollars) in the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the Finance Ministry, the government has pegged
the fiscal target for 1999-2000 fiscal at 799.95 billion rupees
(18.60 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
This was only 7 percent higher than the 747.37 billion rupees
(17.38 billion U.S. dollars) reported in the revised estimates for
1998-1999 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The higher fiscal deficit was caused by continued sluggishness
of revenue receipts to the Exchequer, which failed to contain the
spurt in expenditure witnessed right through the current fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
The government's total expenditure in the first five months of
the current fiscal year shot up nearly 17 percent to 1,017.54
billion rupees (23.66 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, net revenue receipts rose only by 9 percent to 506.11
billion rupees (11.77 billion U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
