<HEADLINE> Eight People Killed in Karachi Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 1 (Xinhua) -- At least eight people were
killed and four others injured Friday morning when two
unidentified persons opened fire on a Shiite Muslim Mosque in
Pakistan's southern port city of Karachi.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman from Tehrik-e-Jafria, a religious party, said that
four unidentified persons came to the mosque named Iman Bargah in
the city's eastern district with weapons. Two entered the mosque
while two others stood outside.
</P>
<P>
They opened fire indiscriminately against the people who were
offering morning pray, killing at least eight people on the spot.
</P>
<P>
The bodies of the dead and the injured were shifted to nearby
Fauji Foundation Hospital.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in central Punjab town of Multan, a Shiite Muslim
named Akhtar Hussain was shot dead by two unidentified
motorcyclists Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
Eye-witnesses from Multan said that Akhtar Hussain was sitting
in his shop, the Raza Bakers, and was attending a customer when
two persons came on a motorbike and sprayed the shopkeeper with
bullets. Hussain died on the spot.
</P>
<P>
No one has so far claimed responsibility for the incidents and
police have made no arrests.
</P>
<P>
It was the fourth incident of sectarian killings in Pakistan
during the last three days. At least four people were killed in
the sectarian violence in the three days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
