<HEADLINE> Beijing in Festive Mood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital has been
saturated with a festive mood, though a grand ceremony to
celebrate the 50th anniversary of the founding of the People's
Republic of China has just ended.
</P>
<P>
The grand military and civilian parade has impressed the
Beijing residents very much and they can not help talking about it
with whoever and whenever and wherever they meet.
</P>
<P>
"I saw all the weapons in the parade and feel very much
encouraged," said Ms. Li Xiulian who lives in the Dongcheng
District of Beijing, "Our country is now really powerful and the
life of the Chinese people has improved remarkably."
</P>
<P>
Shoppers watched the parade on TV in department stores,
shopping malls and supermarkets, which still open today. "Just
look at the new products and achievements we have made, very
exciting!" said one shopper who gave only his surname Liu.
</P>
<P>
He added that beginning this year, we have three days more for
the holidays and this also shows the growth of the country's
economy and the improvement of our life quality."
</P>
<P>
At the Beijing Railway Station, passengers were watching the
National Day celebrations on a large-screen TV. "I'm so lucky to
have arrived in Beijing on the National Day," said one passenger
traveling on business.
</P>
<P>
In a restaurant, a group of youngsters were commenting the
National Day celebrations over their lunch, saying that they are
so happy to see so many state-of-the-art weapons China now is able
to manufacture. "My friends abroad have sent me e-mails saying
that this year's National Day celebrations must be very exciting,
and they are right," one of them said.  
