<HEADLINE> Life-long Dream Realized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- In the accompaniment of the tune
"Good Life", a folk song, Beijing residents today joined the
parade in a square formation, moving past the Tian'anmen Square to
celebrate the 50th anniversary of the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
They included a couple in their 60s who could hardly conceal
their excitement while talking to Xinhua. "It's been a dream all
our lives to take part in the 50th anniversary celebrations," the
woman, Sun Yunyou, said.
</P>
<P>
Sun broke her leg this March, but recovered with the help of
her husband, Peng Junzhou, who is a doctor. In the past they would
have been too busy to join such activities, but this time they
were able to get free.
</P>
<P>
The couple became involved in the Communist Party-led
revolutionary activities at a young age and shared a profound love
for new China. In 1949, when the People's Republic was founded,
they went to Dalian separately to look for work.
</P>
<P>
In Dalian, people were dancing to the music of folk songs to
celebrate the founding of the People's Republic. "It was like
someone catching sight of the brightness after a long journey in
the darkness," Peng recalls, "dancing and singing with incredible
delight."
</P>
<P>
In Dalian, they met, fell in love, got married, and eventually
had three daughters.
</P>
<P>
They are natives of Beijing and returned to the capital in the
mid-1980s after retirement and they are now leading a happy life.
She spends her time singing, painting, and reading, and he loves
swimming, listening to music, and collecting odd stones. They are
both members of a local choir group for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
Travel has become another hobby of theirs and they say that it
is making up for missed lessons. They have visited Sichuan and
Yunnan provinces and the city of Shenzhen, not to mention one
foreign country -- Thailand.
</P>
<P>
"We have spent our best years together in the motherland," Peng
says, "We can work for the motherland for another 20 years, even
if we are becoming older."  
</P>
</TEXT>
