<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Veteran Soldier Cherishes Memory of New China's Founding Ceremony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- At the age of 70, Liu Baoqin
retained his bearing of a soldier in the National Day parade here
today, as a member of a square formation of local residents in the
Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
Fifty years ago he was a soldier and had taken part in the
parade to celebrate the founding of the People's Republic of China
(PRC), as one of the military paraders.
</P>
<P>
"I was standing in front of the Tian'anmen Rostrum and the
Tian'anmen Square was a sea of people," he recalled.
</P>
<P>
The founding ceremony started at 3:00 pm, on October 1, 1949. "
I could not see what happened on the rostrum as I was standing
with my back against it, but I tried hard to listen," he said.
</P>
<P>
When Chairman Mao Zedong declared the founding of the PRC, the
crowds began to shout, "Long live Chairman Mao! Long live the
Communist Party of China (CPC)!", Liu said.
</P>
<P>
"The people's government is hard-won and numerous martyrs had
sacrificed their lives for it," he said.
</P>
<P>
Liu joined the Eighth Route Army, a CPC-led anti-Japanese armed
force, at 15 and since 1949, he worked as a bodyguard for central
leaders. He has retired from the local housing management bureau
in the city's Dongcheng District and has a big family of 14,
including his grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
When Liu applied to participate in this year's parader, someone
doubted his ability to walk a long way in the procession.
</P>
<P>
"I'm in good health," he said, "I must take part in this year's
National Day parade, it is a rare chance for me now."
</P>
<P>
"I represent 190 million aged people in China," he said proudly.
</P>
<P>
The founding of the People's Republic of China, especially the
reform and opening drive, have brought about great changes in the
country, he said, adding, "The people's life is improving day by
day." 
</P>
</TEXT>
