<HEADLINE> Elderly Chinese Woman Joins In National Day Celebrations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Jia Xiulin, 71, joined today's
hundreds of thousands of paraders marching past Beijing's
Tian'anmen Rostrum on National Day and she is perhaps the most
experienced parader.
</P>
<P>
Jia has taken part in the National Day celebrations for 12
years in the past five decades. "I'm strong enough to beat my
granddaughter in a long walk," she said, crediting the army for
her phenomenal walking ability. During the war, she sometimes had
to walk all night for 120 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
However, her participation in the original ceremony was just a
matter of luck. On October 1, 1949, Jia and her husband, who lived
in the neighboring Hebei Province, were headed elsewhere via
Beijing, but they were taken to Tian'anmen Square by friends, not
knowing that there would be a large ceremony for the founding of
the People's Republic of China. Telecommunications were not so
great in those days, she recalled.
</P>
<P>
It was too late to join the parade but they did hear Chairman
Mao Zedong announcing the founding of the People's Republic. They
were so excited hearing Mao's voice for the first time, she said,
because they had fought bloody battles for that day.
</P>
<P>
This year, Jia did well in the training and rehearsals for the
parade, in fact, the entire team of elderly surprised other people
this year, according to the organizers.
</P>
<P>
"I'll let you in on a secret," Jia said confidentially, "I
climbed mountains several times before this parade." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
