<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Manages to Halt Nuclear Chain Reaction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 1 (Xinhua) -- A nuclear chain reaction was
averted at a uranium processing plant in Tokaimura, Ibaraki
Prefecture, after a major nuclear accident occurred there Thursday,
Japanese government said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The government's task force said the neutron monitor at the
plant site registered zero as of 6:15 a.m., signifying that a
chain reaction had been prevented.
</P>
<P>
The volume of neutrons being emitted at 4 a.m. was 0.7
millisievert per hour, about one-fifth that observed at midnight
Thursday, the Science and Technology agency said.
</P>
<P>
Instructions to evacuate remained in effect within a radius of
350 meters around the plant Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
High levels of radiation leaked from the uranium processing
plant at around 10:35 a.m. Thursday. Three workers were exposed to
the radiation, two of them were in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
The victims were all employees of Tokyo-based JCO Co.,
previously called Japan Nuclear Fuel Conversion Co., which runs
the facility.
</P>
<P>
Employees of JCO Co. began removing water coolant at the plant
at 2:58 a.m. and later had to destroy the coolant-water pipes
because drainage valves were not functioning properly, the agency
said.
</P>
<P>
Just after 9 a.m., the workers began preparations to inject
boron chemicals, usually used in control rods in nuclear reactors,
into the facility in an attempt to control and restrain the
nuclear fission reaction.
</P>
<P>
Three firefighters, 16 JCO employees and seven people around
the plant were later confirmed to have been exposed, bringing the
total number of people affected to 36.
</P>
<P>
The leak, which was believed to be Japan's worst-ever nuclear
accident, prompted Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi to
postpone a cabinet reshuffle, originally scheduled for Friday, to
deal with the crisis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Rejects Outside Intervention in Drug Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, September 30 (Xinhua)-- The visiting Colombian Vice-
President Gustavo Bell reaffirmed Thursday that Colombia will not
accept direct interference from other countries in its internal
affairs, including its fight against drugs.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference, Bell admitted that international
cooperation on the fight against drugs would be welcomed, if under
the command of Colombian authorities.
</P>
<P>
The vice president, who came here on Tuesday for a three-day
visit, said that one of the biggest problems Colombia is facing is
drug-trafficking, a crime that affects the world. He announced the
creation of a fund to fight the evil with support of the
international community.
</P>
<P>
Bell said his visit formed part of a Colombian strategy to
speak about the peace process in his country. He added that
President Andres Pastrana's government will renew talks next week
with guerrilla forces, including Revolutionary Armed Forces of
Colombia (FARC) and the National Liberation Army (ELN). 
