<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian New Legislators Sworn in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- New members of the People's
Consultative Assembly (MPR), Indonesia's highest decision-making
body, were sworn in here on Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
The 700 members of the MPR comprise 462 House of
Representatives (DPR) members elected in the June 7 polls, 38
representatives of the Indonesian Military and National Police,
135 regional representatives and 65 representatives of various
interest groups.
</P>
<P>
However, not all the 700 members turned up for the induction
ceremony. General Elections Commission Secretary Samad Thahir said
a number of regional representatives from East Timor, Aceh and
Southeast Sulawesi and other provinces missed the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The oath-taking was led by Chief Justice Sarwata and witnessed
by President B.J. Habibie.
</P>
<P>
As the members of the MPR began their duty, a 21,000-strong
security force was well-prepared to safeguard the city.
</P>
<P>
No less than 6,000 soldiers and police officers were seen
occupying their posts within and near the MPR/DPR building.
Hundreds of military tents have been set up in several areas in
the vicinity of the building.
</P>
<P>
The General Session of MPR consists of two phases. Following
the oath taking ceremony, the new members will form a working
group and factions, deliberate on outlining the state's broad
guidelines (GBHN) and amending the constitution, and then
determine the specific dates for the next phase, which will
include electing a new president and endorsing the national
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
The current schedule puts the presidential election in
November. However, most major political parties have demanded that
the MPR session be held ahead of the original schedule in order to
end the present uncertainty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
