<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Non-public Sectors Represented in Anniversary Parade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Walking in the square formation
of Beijing residents, the 40 paraders representing non-public
sectors start to wave bouquets cheerfully as they come near the
Tian'anmen Rostrum.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that people from non-public economies
are represented in an anniversary parade as an important component
of the socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
They are from a dozen lines of businesses including catering,
entertainment, garment manufacturing, commerce and trade, and
technology development. They represent the more than 20 million
prospering private businesses in China.
</P>
<P>
The Ninth National People's Congress passed an amendment to the
Constitution last March, which raised the status of non-public
sectors to "an important component of the socialist market economy
" from the past definition of being "a complement to the socialist
public economy".
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1998, more than 1.2 million private enterprises
had been registered at the industrial and commercial departments.
The number of individual businessmen has exceeded 31.2 million.
The amount of taxes they turned in last year made up 8.5 percent
of the country's total commercial and industrial tax revenue.
</P>
</TEXT>
