<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Government to Set up Labor Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government is
working to form a bank for laborers, the Kathmandu Post quoted a
government official as saying Friday.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Labor Bal Bahadur K.C. said Thursday that the
government will set up the bank for laborers in partnership with
the foreign employment agencies.
</P>
<P>
"The government is preparing to from a Foreign Employment Bank
for the welfare of the laborers," said Bahadur K.C. "The bank will
grant loans at a low interest rate to the poor laborers who seek
foreign employment."
</P>
<P>
Bahadur also said the government is developing a new system to
make the licensing process for foreign employment easy and smooth
and to discourage incidents of swindling.
</P>
<P>
"There has been a steady decline in cases of swindling in the
foreign employment since the past few months because of the
government's new system," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister cited Foreign Employment Regulation 1999 which was
passed in the recently concluded 16th session of the House of
Representatives as an example of the government's commitment
towards solving the problem.
</P>
<P>
"If the provisions of the regulation are implemented
effectively, it will prevent people from being duped while seeking
foreign employment," he said.
</P>
<P>
To alleviate the pressure of unemployment in the country, the
Nepali government encourages foreign employment of Nepalese
people. According to Labor Ministry, around 20,000 Nepalese are
working in the Gulf region, and 10,000 in Malaysia who entered the
country illegally.
</P>
<P>
Many Nepalese going abroad to seek fortune are cheated by
employment agencies because of lack of sound regulations and
ignorance of the people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
