<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2,000-Year-Old Bamboo Records Found In Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Some 1,000 bamboo strips that
were used before paper was invented and that have beautifully
written Chinese characters on them have been found in a Western
Han Dynasty (206 B.C.-A.D. 24 ) tomb in China's Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
The tomb is that of Wu Yang, a high-ranking official of
Yuanling Prefecture in the western part of the province. The
bamboo records are for household registration, taxes, historical
events, and imperial recipes, according to Hu Pingsheng, of the
Chinese Relics Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
He says that the household record is from an earlier period
than that found in Gansu Province's Dunhuang and Juyan early this
century, which was the first bamboo strip found in China.
</P>
<P>
The number of households, individuals, and weapons, the size of
fields, and the amount of taxes in Yuanling Prefecture in early
Western Han Dynasty is given in great detail, Hu says. Even the
roads and posthouses on the way to Chang'an, the capital of the
Western Han, in present-day Shaanxi Province, are recorded.
</P>
<P>
More can be discovered from the strips but it takes time and
money, Guo Weimin, an archeologist with the Hunan Relics Research
Institute, points out.
</P>
<P>
He says that a large number of bamboo strips found early this
century were smuggled out of the country. The largest find so far
has been in Changsha, Hunan's capital, in 1996, where some 170,000
records dating back to the Three Kingdoms (220-280) were unearthed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
