<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Newspapers Hail China's Glorious Past </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Many of Hong Kong newspapers
Friday carry stories and editorials to celebrate China's National
Day, hailing the great achievements China has made over the past
half century and looking into the country's bright future.
</P>
<P>
In its editorial on the 50th anniversary of the founding of the
People's Republic of China, Ta Kung Po says that on the occasion
of celebration, China showed the whole world not only the
brilliant history of the past but also the bright future of the
nation in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
Wen Wei Po says in an article that over the past 50 years,
China's comprehensive national strength and the standards of
living of millions of Chinese have been greatly improved.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper says that after bidding farewell to the history
of backwardness and semi-feudalism, China has entered a stage of
rejuvenating the great Chinese nation.
</P>
<P>
The "one country, two systems" concept is a feasible and
correct principle of fulfilling China's reunification, the
newspaper says, adding that Hong Kong's former social and economic
systems and its lifestyle all remain unchanged and the rights and
freedoms of Hong Kong people prescribed in the HK Special
Administrative Region Basic Law are fully guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
With the concerted efforts of the Chinese people at home and
overseas, the complete reunification of the motherland and the
overall invigoration of the Chinese nation will surely come true,
the newspaper says.
</P>
<P>
Other major newspapers in Hong Kong Friday also carry reports
to highlight the important event.
</P>
<P>
South China Morning Post says in a report that China has
changed beyond all recognition over the past half century. A
backward and semi-feudal nation has been transformed into the
world's fastest-growing economy, it says.
</P>
<P>
Sing Tao daily also carries a piece marking China's National
Day, saying that China has made major achievements in the
development of its economy over the past 20 years since it
implemented the policy of reforms and opening up, and it will
certainly become one of the strongest economies so long as it
upholds this policy. 
</P>
