<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grand March-Past Starts As Military Band Strikes Up A March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua)-- The military band strikes up a
march and a guard of honor of the People's Liberation Army (PLA)
three services start marching past the Tiananmen Rostrum at parade
step.
</P>
<P>
This marks the beginning of the grand march-past marking the 50
th anniversary of the People's Republic of China (PRC).
</P>
<P>
At the head of the honor guard is 1.88-meter-tall Song Yueqiang
with a red army flag in hand and accompanied by two flag escorts.
</P>
<P>
It is this guard of honor that raised the national flag for the
first time in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region at
midnight of July 1, 1997, when Hong Kong returned to the
motherland.
</P>
<P>
The guard of honor consists of a total of 156 PLA men, whose
average height is 1.84 meters, the tallest among all square
formations.
</P>
<P>
The guard of honor of the PLA three services, which was set up
in 1951 for important ceremonies, has accomplished more than 2,000
major tasks and enjoys high prestige both at home and abroad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Future Generals" Formation Marching Past Tiananmen Rostrum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Cadets in field-grade uniforms, who come from the University of
National Defense, China's highest military academy, are the first
to parade after the honor guard of the People's Liberation Army (
PLA) three services.
</P>
<P>
Known as the "cradle of generals", the university trains
ranking commanders, staff officers and military theoreticians and
is the Alma Mater of more than 90 percent of China's high-ranking
generals still in active service in the army.
</P>
<P>
The square formation is composed of cadets from the
university's major departments, who belong to nine ethnic groups,
and are expected to become the backbone of the Chinese army in the
21th century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Formations of Military Academies Marching Past Tiananmen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The three academies, aimed at training middle and low-ranking
PLA command officers, are the Shijiazhuang Army Command Academy in
north China's Hebei Province, the Dalian Naval Vessel Academy in
northeast China, and the Beijing Airforce Command Academy.
</P>
<P>
The PLA military academies and schools have trained some 18
million officers over the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
Conspicuous in the military academies formations are the naval
cadets, who wear white uniforms, caps, shoes and waistbands. They
are just like a silver-colored torrent rolling through the
Chang'an boulevard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PLA Sailors: Youngest Formation in Military Parade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Consisting of soldiers aged between 18 and 19, the square
formation is the youngest in the military parade. They are all
students of the same naval submarine academy.
</P>
<P>
Some 60 percent of these young sailors are the single child in
their families, as a result of the nation's family planning policy
which was adopted at the beginning of the 1980s. Their high morale
and strict discipline indicate that they are not spoiled. After
being tempered in the PLA, they are ready to shoulder their
responsibilities as soldiers to defend the motherland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
