<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Feature: Five-Star Red Flag Flying Over China Forever </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- A grand rally is being held in
the Chinese capital this morning to mark the 50th anniversary of
the founding of the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
The celebrations began with a national flag-raising ceremony at
around 10 o'clock in Tian'anmen Square. Accompanied by a 50-gun
salute, 200 flag guards in olive green suits marched across a red
carpet stretching north of the platform of the Monument to the
Memory of the People's Heroes through the square.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese national anthem was playing as the five-star red
flag rose up the 30-meter flagpole, and has remained fluttering in
the gentle autumn breeze.
</P>
<P>
Han Ruqi, chairman of the Beijing Municipal Committee of the
Revolutionary Committee of the Chinese Kuomintang (RCCK), watched
the flag-raising ceremony from a reviewing stand adjacent to the
Tian'anmen Rostrum.
</P>
<P>
"The ideals of the Three People's Principles (nationalism,
democracy and the people's livelihood) put forward by Dr. Sun Yat-
sen have been materialized by the Chinese Communist Party members
and never before in history has China been so prosperous and
strong," he said.
</P>
<P>
A Beijing middle school student Qin Haiyan, who joined the
crowd at the square, said: "This is an exciting moment. Seeing the
hoisting of the national flag, I feel my sense of responsibility
to the motherland is also growing. A reunified and prosperous
China depends on our efforts and contributions."
</P>
<P>
Wu Qi, 69, an automation professor with the prestigious Qinghua
University, said: "With the implementation of the strategy of
vitalizing the country through science and education, I believe
China will achieve miracles and become one of the world's economic
powers in the next century."
</P>
<P>
Jackson Leung S.M., a Hong Kong businessman, said the raising
of the national flag made him feel proud. "A strong China will
play an important role in safeguarding world peace."
</P>
<P>
William Ho, brother of Edmund Ho Hau Wah, first chief executive-
designate of the future Macao Special Administrative Region (MSAR),
said this was the first time he had watched the flag-raising at
Tian'anmen Square.
</P>
<P>
"I am counting the days before the arrival of December 20, when
Macao will be returned to China and pray for an early realization
of the reunification of the motherland," Ho added.
</P>
<P>
Fifty years ago, Mao Zedong, founder of the people's republic,
raised the first national flag of New China by pressing a button.
The five-star national flag of New China was raised for the first
time at the United Nations headquarters in 1971 and later at
numerous other international events.
</P>
<P>
The lifting and lowering of the national flag, which is done at
dawn and dusk every day in Beijing, was previously handled by two
civilians. In 1976, soldiers took over the task.
</P>
<P>
By now, well over three million people watch the national flag-
raising ceremony at Tian'anmen Square each year, said sources from
the Tian'anmen Administrative Committee.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
