<HEADLINE> Flag Raising Ceremony Held in HK for National Day Celebrations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 1 (Xinhua) -- A flag raising ceremony was
held here Friday morning, the first of a series of activities to
mark the 50th anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic
of China (PRC) in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR)
.
</P>
<P>
Elsie Leung, acting chief executive of the SAR, attended the
ceremony, which was held at the seafront promenade outside the
Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Center Extension.
</P>
<P>
HKSAR Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa, leading a 200-member
delegation, is now in Beijing for national day celebrations held
in the capital.
</P>
<P>
Among some 500 participants at the flag raising ceremony were
senior SAR government officials, officials of the Central
Government in Hong Kong, officers of the People's Liberation Army
garrison in the SAR and noted local figures and foreign consuls in
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
After the national flag of the PRC and the flag of the HKSAR
were hoisted at 8:00 a.m. by Hong Kong police officers amidst the
playing of the national anthem of the PRC, helicopters carrying
the flags flew overhead.
</P>
<P>
The flag raising ceremony attracted thousands of residents.
Holding miniature versions of the Chinese national flag and the
HKSAR flag in their hands, they cheered as the five-starred
national flag was hoisted.
</P>
<P>
A young student said that two years after Hong Kong returned to
the motherland, he noticed almost no change in the way of life of
Hong Kong people. "However, I learned much more about China than
before," he said.
</P>
<P>
A retired worker said that he felt a strong sense of pride when
he saw the flags hoisted. "China has made great progress these
years," he said. "I feel proud to be Chinese."
</P>
<P>
Many said that they will go back home to watch the live
television broadcast of the grand parade which will be staged on
the Tiananmen Square in Beijing later Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
Various activities have been staged in Hong Kong to mark China'
s national day in the past months. Gala gatherings will be held at
several places in Hong Kong later Friday and the celebration may
reach its climax as fireworks light up the sky over the Victoria
Harbor Friday night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
