<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chile, Argentina Sign Social Security Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Labor ministers from the
governments of Chile and Argentina signed an accord on Thursday
creating a social security system that assures equality of
treatment for Chileans and Argentineans living in each other's
countries.
</P>
<P>
A bilateral social security treaty was signed in 1996 to
replace an agreement signed in 1971, which benefited only those
individuals who contributed to the social security systems in both
countries.
</P>
<P>
The present treaty will provide modifications within both
countries' social security systems.
</P>
<P>
The new accord, which will benefit 300,000 Chileans living in
Argentina (and Argentineans living in Chile), stipulates that the
two countries social security systems will recognize and honor
payments made into their systems by Chilean or Argentine workers.
</P>
<P>
Thus, people living and working in either Chile or Argentina
will be able to make the requisite payments in either country in
order to have access to old age, disability and survival pensions,
in addition to having access to health benefits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
