<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico City's Subway Ranks Third in the World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Mexico City's subway
system ranks third in the world due in part to the number of daily
passengers and its size, second only to subway systems in Moscow
and Tokyo, Raul Gonzalez, general director of the network said on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The "System of Collective Transport Metro" in Mexico City
serves five million passengers every day in the metropolitan area,
where nearly 20 million people live. 1.825 billion passengers ride
the capital's subway every year, said Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
In Mexico, only the three most important cities have subway
systems: the capital, Guadalajara, in the west and Monterey,
located in the north.
</P>
<P>
Authorities are discussing the possibility of introducing the "
metro" to other cities, such as Tijuana and Baja California Norte,
on the border with United States, or Leon, in Guanajuato state,
located in the central-west region of Mexico, said Gonzalez.
</P>
</TEXT>
