<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0325 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. New-Home Sales Rise in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The Commerce Department
said Thursday that sales of new single-family homes unexpectedly
jumped 2.9 percent in August to a seasonally adjusted annual rate
of 983,000 units, the second-highest level on record.
</P>
<P>
August's increase occurred despite rising mortgage rates and
surprised analysts expecting a decline. In July, 955,000 units
were sold, reflecting a sharp downward revision from the
department's previous estimate.
</P>
<P>
Sales were up in all parts of the country except the South. The
median price for a new home in August was 150,800 dollars, down
from 157,000 dollars in July. But the average home price hit a
record high of 198,300 last month.
</P>
<P>
Through August of this year, there were 659,000 houses sold
compared with 618,000 sold during the same period last year, the
department said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
