<HEADLINE> Beijing Rises Early Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Sanitation workers are generally
thought to be the earliest risers in the morning in Beijing.
However Today, Zhou Weimin rose even earlier than they did.
</P>
<P>
"I didn't mean to compete with anybody in getting up. The fact
is I simply couldn't sleep long as something special has been
lingering in my mind," the middle school teacher said.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the whole Beijing rose earlier than usual this morning,
and some could not even fall asleep because of looking forward
eagerly to seeing the red letter day celebrations.
</P>
<P>
Dang Liang, a senior student of the People's University of
China who rose two hours earlier than usual, is excitedly waving
the bunting to attract attention. "Just think of how many people
across the country will be looking at us! And on this occasion, I
really feel pride being a member of the big family of our
motherland."
</P>
<P>
In the city's oldest lane of Zhuanta, a kilometer from the
square, septuagenarian Li Wenhui, who took part in the parade
marking the founding of new China on October 1, 1949, has begun
doing morning exercises. "Not quite nimble, otherwise I would
prefer to join in today's parade."
</P>
<P>
Durk Jager, president and chief executive officer of Procter &AMP;
Gamble (P&AMP;G) of the United States, is one of the world business
leaders invited to get on the reviewing stands of Tian'anmen
Square to watch the parade.
</P>
<P>
The American, who attended the just-ended Fortune Global Forum
in Shanghai, said: "I believe that a more open and prosperous
China will offer great potential for our business, and we expect
to grow and prosper hand in hand with China."  
</P>
</TEXT>
