<HEADLINE> U.S. Star Gymnast to Miss World Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Dominique Moceanu, one of
American female stars of the 1996 Olympics, won't be competing in
the World Gymnastics Championships on October 8-16 in Tianjin,
China, due to a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
The 18-year-old, who is a member of the title-winning team in
Atlanta, is rehabilitating her right knee after having
arthroscopic surgery in August. She plans to practice her routines
in November for the 2000 Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
But the USA hopes new stars emerge in the world championships,
which is one year before the 2000 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. women and men must place in the top 12 to qualify for
the Summer Games in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
Leading the women's team is Kristen Maloney, the two-time
defending national champion, and Vanessa Atler, the two-time
national runner-up. Both missed world tryouts with injuries but
used past performances to make the team. They are expected to be
close to top form.
</P>
<P>
The rest of the women's team: Elise Ray, Jennie Thompson,
Jeanette Antolin and Jamie Dantzscher.
</P>
<P>
Blaine Wilson, the only man to win four consecutive national
titles, leads the men's team, which is chasing its first Worlds
medal since 1983.
</P>
<P>
Their job got much tougher when Jason Gatson, ranked second
behind Wilson, tore the anterior cruciate ligament in his right
knee on his dismount from the high bar last month.
</P>
<P>
The Most experienced U.S. gymnast is John Roethlisberger, who
is going strong at 29. This will be his fifth Worlds.
</P>
<P>
The rest of the men's team: Yewki Tomita, Sean Townsend, Chris
Young and Stephen McCain. 
</P>
