<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jazz Re-Sign Free Guards Stockton And Hornacek </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The Utah Jazz Thursday re-
signed free agent guards John Stockton and Jeff Hornacek in Salt
Lake City.
</P>
<P>
Stockton received a two-year deal worth 22 million U.S. dollars
and Hornacek signed a one-year, 5.2 million U.S. dollars contract.
The negotiations went smoothly since both players said they had no
intention of leaving Utah.
</P>
<P>
"A lot of faith has grown over the years with the Jazz," said
the 37-year-old Stockton at Thursday's news conference. "I really
had a restful summer, although I was unemployed all the time."
</P>
<P>
The 36-year-old Hornacek said: "We just figured out a fair
number and it takes about 20 minutes to do it when you're
realistic about things."
</P>
<P>
Earlier this offseason, the Jazz re-signed NBA Most Valuable
Player Karl Malone to a four-year, 67 million U.S. dollars
contract. However, the team did lose forward Shandon Anderson, who
signed a free agent contract with the Houston Rockets on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
With the aging nucleus of Malone, Stockton and Hornacek, the
Jazz will attempt to return to the NBA Finals after losing in the
second round of the playoffs to the Portland Trail Blazers last
year.
</P>
<P>
Utah won the Western Conference title in 1997 and 1998, but
lost in the Finals both years to the Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
Stockton is the NBA's all-time leader in assists and steals and
has been Utah's floor leader since the Jazz selected him in the
first round of the 1984 draft.
</P>
<P>
A nine-time All-Star, Stockton averaged 11.1 points and 7.5
rebounds during the lockout-shortened 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
Stockton's best season was 1989-90, when he averaged 17.2
points and a career-high 14.5 assists. He played in 609
consecutive games, third longest streak in league history, before
missing the beginning of last season with a knee injury and was co-
MVP with Malone at the 1993 All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
Hornacek will be entering his sixth full season in Utah and is
coming off his least-productive campaign since averaging 9.5
points in his second year with the Phoenix Suns in 1987-88. He
battled through chronic knee problems and averaged 12.2 points, 4.
0 assists and 3.3 rebounds last season.
</P>
<P>
Hornacek is one of the league's top free throw and 3-point
shooters and was Utah's second-leading scorer for five straight
seasons after coming over in a trade with the Philadelphia 76ers
midway through the 1993-94 campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
