<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1-11 Tian'anmen Square Ready for National Day Celebrations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Tian'anmen Square, the world's
largest urban square, looks even more magnificent and solemn today
as it awaits the grand celebrations marking the 50th anniversary
of the People's Republic of China (PRC).
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of potted flowers have turned the square into
a mammoth garden in the center of the Chinese capital. Meanwhile,
the whole city is decorated with millions of potted flowers. The
national flags can be seen all over the city.
</P>
<P>
Some 500,000 people, including servicemen and civilians, are
gathered at the square and its adjacent streets, waiting for the
exciting moment.
</P>
<P>
As always, the Tian'anmen Rostrum is eye-catching with eight
large-size red lanterns and a glittering national emblem in the
middle. A huge portrait of the late Chairman Mao Zedong hangs over
the main gate of the rostrum.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the two reviewing stands on both sides of the
rostrum, temporary visitors' stands have been set up.
</P>
<P>
High above the square, 34 lantern-like balloons, five to seven
meters in diameter, and two huge floral-basket-shaped balloons are
floating in the air, while colorful banners are flying on
surrounding buildings.
</P>
<P>
A large portrait of Dr. Sun Yat-sen, forerunner of the Chinese
revolution, has been erected right in front of the Monument to
People's Heroes, with one slogan standing at each side of the
portrait.
</P>
<P>
One slogan reads, "Celebrate the 50th Anniversary of the
founding of the People's Republic of China." The other reads, "
Hold high the great banner of Deng Xiaoping Theory and march
toward the new century."
</P>
<P>
Red carpets have been spread on the grounds between the
monument and the pole of the National Flag, and between the Golden-
Water Bridge in front of the rostrum, and the main gate of rostrum.
</P>
<P>
A countdown board in front of the Museum of the Chinese
Revolution indicates that the long-awaited resumption of the
exercise of sovereignty over Macao by China on December 20, 1999,
is merely 80 days away. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0339 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Why Southeast Asian Currencies Fall Again? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- There has been seemingly a
contradictory phenomenon in Asia's foreign exchange markets in
recent weeks: While the Japanese yen has climbed to its 40-month
high to the greenback, Southeast Asian currencies dropped to their
lowest levels in six or 10 months.
</P>
<P>
As Southeast Asia's major trading partner and creditor, Japan's
currency strength always has a direct impact on other East Asian
currencies. In August last year, when the Japanese yen fell to 147
to the dollar, East Asian currencies all depreciated to their
lowest in years.
</P>
<P>
And when the yen started to rebound later last year, the
regional currencies also began to gain strengthen. In the first
half of this year, Southeast Asian currencies have gained around
10 to 50 percent, partly due to the faster-than-expected regional
economic recovery, and partly due to the strong yen.
</P>
<P>
But recently, the situation is quite different. when the yen
maintained its 106 level against the dollar Thursday, other East
Asian currencies remained weak.
</P>
<P>
The Thai baht plunged to a year low of around 41 against the
greenback Thursday, and the Philippine peso also closed near the
41 to the dollar level, the lowest in 10 months.
</P>
<P>
Why did the regional currencies fail to respond to the yen's
upward trend?
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the slide in Southeast Asian currencies,
which started as early as in June, was caused mainly by different
domestic factors and problems within the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
For instance, they said, the baht's recent decline was blamed
on foreign currency purchase to fund Thai companies' repayment of
yen-denominated debt, due at the end of the quarter.
</P>
<P>
In the Philippines, the narrowing differential between
Philippine and U.S. interest rates has triggered dollar buying on
the spot market recently as investors shifted out of peso assets.
</P>
<P>
In addition to domestic factors, Southeast Asian countries'
currencies have been weakened by a problem at their doorstep --
the political situation in Indonesia rocked by unrest in Jakarta
and the East Timor.
</P>
<P>
"If the situation in Indonesia does not improve and the rupiah
falls through the 9,500 (level against the dollar) and extends its
weakness beyond 10,000, there will be a psychological negative
impact on the rest of the currencies," said Philip Wee, a regional
economist at Standard Chartered Bank in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
As domestic issues are the major cause of weak currencies in
the region, the strong yen, which rose to 103 in mid-September to
the dollar, has not had any significant impact on them.
</P>
<P>
But as Southeast Asian nations are rivals in trade, one
currency's sharp fall will force other currencies in the region to
maintain their weakness in order to achieve competitiveness in the
regional and international markets.
</P>
<P>
Because of this, once one Southeast Asian country's currency
falls, other regional currencies will be dragged down.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, authorities in the region are not worried about
the sharp fall in their currencies, since almost all these
countries are trying to maintain export competitiveness with weak
currencies.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government has recently shown themselves readier to
accept a weaker baht in the interest of trade competitiveness.
Thai Deputy Finance Minister Pisit Leeahtam said last Thursday
that the government was unconcerned at the prospect of baht
depreciation beyond 40 to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
"The central banks have all stood aside and let the market take
the currencies weaker. They are not unhappy with the situation,"
said Vincent Low, a regional economist at Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
In the Philippines, the central bank pushed for higher interest
rates to curb the peso's fall in the past. But now, despite the
peso's slide, the government said that it will cut further
interest rates to match levels in the United States and its Asian
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that since Southeast Asian countries have no plan
to intervene in foreign exchange markets, the regional currencies
are expected to maintain their weakness in the weeks ahead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
