<HEADLINE> Parade to Review China's Achievements in 50 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- China's achievements in the past
five decades will be demonstrated in today's grand military and
civilian parade marking the 50th anniversary of the founding of
new China.
</P>
<P>
The achievements will show how the Chinese people have gone all
out to build a socialist State with burgeoning prosperity after
they became masters of their own destiny.
</P>
<P>
Floats and sculptures in the first part of the parade
formations will show how China relied on its own for development
in such aspects as oil exploration, steel-making and construction
of water control projects, development of atomic bombs, hydrogen
bombs, missiles and satellites.
</P>
<P>
China's rapid economic growth and improvement of people's life
quality and earth-shaking changes in other sectors in the past 20
years since the beginning of reform and opening up will be
illustrated in 12 floats in a large formation.
</P>
<P>
Sculptures and models will also be used to show the Three
Gorges Hydroelectric Power Project, the Wuhan Yangtze River Bridge,
nuclear power stations, robots and wide use of computers in
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
One square formation will also show that China feeds about one
fifth of the world's population with about ten percent of the
world's total arable land. China is the largest steel producer in
the world and is also in the forefront in terms of life expectancy.
</P>
<P>
A huge newly-wed cartoon couple demonstrates China's success in
implementing the family planning policy, which has helped save 7.
40 trillion yuan (about 890 billion U.S. dollars) in child-raising
costs during the past three decades, because 300 million fewer
babies were born in China in the period.
</P>
<P>
The parade will also show China's improvements in cultural life
and the country's successes in education, science, culture and
sports.
</P>
<P>
Conspicuous will be the 2,000-year-old chime bells, one of
China's most precious treasures.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of China's world champions will also pass by the
Tian'anmen Rostrum in a float. By now, China has over 1,200 world
championships and Beijing is now bidding for the right to hold the
Olympic Games in 2008.
</P>
<P>
China's achievements in such fields as astronomy, mathematics,
and bio-engineering will also be shown in the parade. The
education square formation will tell the fact that China's all
school-age children has by and large gone to school and illiteracy
has dropped drastically since the founding of new China.
</P>
<P>
The China's efforts to fight the 1998 devastating flooding will
also be told in a float.
</P>
<P>
Special floats also be used to display China's economic
development objectives by the year of 2050, and to feature Hong
Kong, Macao and Taiwan, suggesting China's reunification.
</P>
<P>
The last float carries a model of spacecraft, indicating that
top priority is given to science and technology in China's
socialist modernization construction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
