<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Indonesian People's Consultative Assembly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The People's Consultative
Assembly (MPR) is Indonesia's highest state institution.
Sovereignty is in the hands of the people and is exercised in full
by the MPR as the embodiment of the whole Indonesian people. The
People's Consultative Assembly is to be distinguished from the
legislative body proper -- House of Representatives or DPR which
is incorporated in the MPR.
</P>
<P>
The MPR has a total of 700 members who serve for five years,
including 500 members of the DPR and 200 presidential appointees
(135 regional representatives and 65 functional representatives).
</P>
<P>
The MPR is required to meet once every 5 years, and its duties
include electing the president and vice president, amending the
Constitution and approving the broad policy aims of the
government.
</P>
<P>
The 500-member DPR exercises legislative authority, with 462
directly elected and 38 reserved for the Armed Forces whose
members do not vote.
</P>
<P>
The DPR meets at least once a year. All laws must have the
approval of the DPR, but the president has absolute veto. Members
of the DPR have the right to submit draft bills which require
ratification by the president. The president may enact ordinance
in times of emergency, which however must be either ratified or
revoked by the DPR at its following session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0346 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: A Chronicle of National Day Military Parades (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On October 1, 1956, 11,929 soldiers and cadets took part in the
parade, who were, to a considerable extent, armed with Chinese-
made weapons, marking a new progress in the country's defense
industry.
</P>
<P>
On October 1, 1957, 7,065 soldiers and cadets as well 266 tanks,
112 guns and 81 warplanes participated in the parade.
</P>
<P>
On October 1, 1958, the military parade consisted of seven
formations of cadets, six formations of infantry soldiers, four
formations of soldiers from other kinds of troops, as well as
eight formations of guns, four formations of tanks, and 93
warplanes.
</P>
<P>
Between 1954 and 1958, then Defense Minister Peng Dehuai
reviewed all the four military parades.
</P>
<P>
On October 1, 1958, 15 formations of soldiers and cadets, 14
formations of vehicles of various kinds, and six squads of
warplanes appeared in the National Day show. A total of 11,018
soldiers and cadets, 144 guns, 99 tanks and self-propelled guns,
240 automobiles and 165 warplanes participated in the parade. Many
new types of arms made their first appearance in the parade.
</P>
<P>
In 1959, Lin Biao replaced Peng Dehuai as the defense minister
and made his first and last review of the National Day parading
troops.
</P>
<P>
On October 1, 1984, Deng Xiaoping, architect of China's reform
and opening policy and then Chairman of the Central Military
Commission reviewed the parading troops -- soldiers and cadets as
well as guns, vehicles and missiles of various kinds, in 46
formations and echelons, and 117 warplanes. Missiles and strategic
missiles were showed to the public for the first time during the
parade. All the weapons and military equipment on display were
home-made, mostly new at the time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991001.0347 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: A Chronicle of National Day Military Parades </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Following is a chronicle of the 12 military parades before this
year's:
</P>
<P>
On October 1, 1949, the parading troops at PRC's founding
ceremony included a long procession of field troops, composed of
infantry, artillery and cavalry soldiers, and a formation of
sailors from the navy and cadets from a navy school. A small fleet
of warplanes including fighter planes, bombers and trainers.
</P>
<P>
On October 1, 1950, the military paraders, totaling 24,200,
included troops and cadets from the infantry, navy and air force
units as well as a division of the public security army. Exhibited
weapons included 88 guns of various kinds, 80 self-propelled guns,
178 vehicles, 2,899 horses, and 28 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
On October 1, 1951, the military parade was formed by 13,348
troops including soldiers and cadets from the infantry, navy, air
force troops as well militia. Also displayed in the parade were
128 guns of various kinds, 80 tanks and self-propelled guns, 192
automobiles, 1,104 horses and 148 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
On October 1, 1952, 57 square formations of soldiers and cadets
from the field, navy and air force units, totalling 11,300, joined
in the procession, together with nine flying squads, including 153
aircraft. Also attending were 112 guns, 99 tanks and self-
propelled guns, 16 armored vehicles, 156 automobiles, 160
tricycles, and 1,104 horses. The parachute troops made their debut
in this National Day rally.
</P>
<P>
On October 1, 1953, the military paraders included 10,038
soldiers and cadets from the infantry, navy, airforce troops,
accompanied by 144 guns, 67 tanks and self-propelled guns, 168
vehicles, 165 tricycles, 770 horses and 96 warplanes.
</P>
<P>
From 1949 to 1953, all the five National Day military parades
were reviewed by Zhu De, then General Commander of the Chinese
People's Liberation Army (PLA).
</P>
<P>
On October 1, 1954, The land procession included 38 formations
of soldiers and cadets, totaling 10,384, from the field, navy and
air force troops as well as the public security troops,
accompanied by a number of tanks, guns as well as 111 warplanes,
in four squads.
</P>
<P>
In the previous five National Day parades, all weapons
displayed were made in different countries, but in the 1954 parade,
the sixth, the soldiers were mostly equipped with Soviet-made arms.
</P>
<P>
On October 1, 1955, soldiers and cadets marched past the
Tiananmen Rostrum in 38 square formations, wearing shoulder-marks
for the first time as China began to adopt a ranking system for
the army that year. Jet-bombers and jet-fighter planes also made
their first show this time. A total of 10,344 soldiers and
officers joined in the military review.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
