<HEADLINE> U.S. 2nd Quarter Growth Slows More Sharply Than  Previously Estimated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. economic growth
slowed to an annual rate of 1.6 percent in the second quarter,
worse than previously estimated and the smallest gain in four
years, according to the Commerce Department's revised report
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Many economists believe the slowdown reported Thursday by the
department was only a brief pause.
</P>
<P>
The 1.6 percent gain in the gross domestic product, the total
output of goods and services, from April through June marked the
slowest growth since the spring of 1995 when the economy grew at a
0.4 percent rate.
</P>
<P>
The second-quarter GDP increase was weaker than the 1.8 percent
rate the department reported one month ago and the 2.3 percent it
had initially estimated in July.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to keep the economy from overheating and prevent
an outbreak of inflation, the Federal Reserve has raised interest
rates twice this summer.
</P>
<P>
Fed policy-makers next meet Oct. 5, and many economists do not
expect another interest-rate increase at that time.
</P>
<P>
An inflation gauge tied to the second-quarter GDP rose 1.9
percent, less than the 2.1 percent the government estimated one
month ago. In the first quarter of this year, that inflation
measure rose 1.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The report said economic growth was reduced by 1.36 percentage
points by a second-quarter trade deficit. That was a bigger
reduction than the estimated loss of 1.34 percentage points in
growth reported by the government last month.
</P>
<P>
During the second quarter the trade deficit swelled to 34.4
billion dollars, a little wider than previously thought, as a 15.1
percent jump in imports overwhelmed a 4.9 percent increase in
exports.
</P>
<P>
The surging trade imbalance reflects the impact of the global
financial crisis, which has cut into U.S. export sales while
increasing competition on U.S. manufacturers from a flood of
cheaper imports. However, with economies in Asia and Latin America
on the mend, foreign demand for U.S. products is picking up.
</P>
<P>
In Thursday's report, the department also said the profits of
U.S. companies decreased at an annual rate of 9.5 billion dollars
in the second quarter, a bigger decline than the 9.2 billion
dollars previously estimated. In the first quarter of the year,
profits rose at a 47.1 billion dollar rate.
</P>
<P>
In addition to facing stiff price competition from imports,
U.S. companies are being pinched by increasing labor costs
resulting from the lowest unemployment rate in 29 years.
</P>
<P>
In another report Thursday, the Labor Department said the
number of people filing for unemployment benefits last week rose
by 25,000 to 299,000.
</P>
<P>
The booming U.S. economy has been powered by robust consumer
spending, which, the department said, rose at an annual rate of
4.8 percent in the second quarter. That compares with an estimated
4.6 percent rate a month ago and with a torrid 6.7 percent pace in
the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
U.S. consumers continue to spend more than they earn, pulling
the nation's personal savings rate to a record low of negative 1.3
percent in the second quarter, the same as previously estimated.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, business investment rose at an annual rate of 10.8
percent in the second quarter. Spending for new homes and
apartments was up at a 7.1 percent rate.
</P>
<P>
All the changes show the economy growing at an annual rate of
31 billion dollars in the second quarter of the year, pushing the
country's total output of goods and services to 7.8 trillion
dollars, after adjusting for inflation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
