<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Rebound Strongly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks rebounded
strongly Thursday as a government report on slower economy eased
fears of the interest rate hike.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 123.47 at 10,336.95,
its second gain in eight tradings.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index rose 14.34 at 1,282.71 and the technology heavy
Nasdaq composite index rose 15.89 at 2,746.16.
</P>
<P>
The market rallied strongly after the Commerce Department
reported that the U.S. economic growth slowed to an annual rate of
1.6 percent in the second quarter from 4.3 percent in the first
quarter. The second-quarter growth increase was weaker than the
1.8 percent rate reported earlier.
</P>
<P>
The new report on economic growth make investors believe that
the Federal Reserve would leave the interest rates alone at a
meeting in Washington on October 5. Concerns with the rate hike
for the third time this year have dragged stocks much lower.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index rose 6.55 at 592.79 and the American Stock
Exchange index rose 8.19 at 788.23. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies rose 5.78 at 427.30.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by an 8-to-5 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange with 1,907 up, 1,193 down and 464
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 1.01 billion shares from 850.86
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
