<HEADLINE> Chinese Businessmen Invited to Invest in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Minister of
State Wilson Masilingi Thursday invited more Chinese businessmen
to invest in his country, promising that they will earn profits.
</P>
<P>
"Our government has taken upon itself the priority task to
create a favorable environment for foreign investment in many
potential areas for mutual rewarding co-operation," Masilingi
said.
</P>
<P>
"We pledge to work hard to make it easier and profitable for
Chinese companies to be more active in Tanzania for mutual
benefit," he added.
</P>
<P>
Masilingi made the remarks while attending a reception to mark
the 50th anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic of
China.
</P>
<P>
The state minister, on behalf of the Tanzanian government,
expressed gratitude to China's assistance over the past years. He
mentioned several projects built with the aid of China, such as
Tanzania-Zambia railway, Mbarari farm, Kiwira coal mine, among
others, as well as training of personnel.
</P>
<P>
"I can just say with justified pride that Tanzania and China are
indeed genuine and old friends," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The senior official said that the friendship and co-operation
between the two countries should become even stronger.
</P>
<P>
He said both China and Tanzania are undergoing economic
reforms, and several Chinese companies have heeded Tanzanian
President Benjamin Mkapa's call and started to invest in the east
African country or set up joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
"While we can be satisfied with the success of economic
co-operation so far achieved, I sincerely believe that there is
still a wide scope for further expansion of co-operation in new
forms and areas of mutual interest in the spirit of south-south
co-operation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese ambassador to Tanzania Wang Yongqiu said that history
has shown that Tanzania and China are all-weather friends and the
two countries will make joint efforts to bring a more dynamic
bilateral relationship of co- operation into the 21st century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
